commit_message:
Update LoDash to 3.9.3

Also move Backbone.DeepModel to a custom libraries - it required
modification to work with newer LoDash, but it is not updated.
Backbone.stickit is updated to 0.9.2 to support newer LoDash.

Change-Id: Ic3a2c64bd73c91d53431c55da9747884bcf6010a

subject: Add PLUMgrid Neutron Plugin to neutron playbooks
messages:
[{'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-05-21 07:37:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-21 07:38:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/26/184726/1/check/gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs/303f480//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 32s'}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-05-21 07:41:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-21 07:42:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/26/184726/2/check/gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs/ca6c962//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 29s'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-05-23 21:20:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'm confused why this is updating master and juno but not kilo. That said, isn't the idea of os-ansible-deployment a vanilla openstack deployment with no proprietary plugins? I say that in reference to kilo and master. Juno is Rackspace technical debt and adding this to that branch/release is fine with me. For Kilo/master, should this work instead be done in rpc-extras?"}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-05-26 19:49:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the review Ian. You're right, I meant this for juno and kilo not master. I wrote it pre-kilo branch, got a bit delayed in committing the spec.

This could indeed be added to the rpc_extras, however some of the main tasks required for PLUMgrid to install have to be done through the neutron playbooks, as it is replacing ml2 with the PLUMgrid plugin. So those changes will touch the main playbooks. The rest of the installation for PLUMgrid elements can then go elsewhere if that seems more appropriate? However the neutron changes by themselves would be meaningless without the rest of the PLUMgrid playbooks."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-05-28 09:43:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

If the spec is changed to provide the facility to include alternative neutron plugins then we can happily approve this. To include one specific plugin that uses a proprietary back-end will not be approved here. That belongs in deployer playbooks/roles (eg: rpc-extras).'}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-05-28 18:34:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 18:38:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Uploaded a new patch, that mentions the target branches to be juno and kilo. Some more detail on the changes required have been put in.

Jesse, this BP change will be dependent on this one: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184665/5

which introduces the said configurability to include alternative neutron plugins. Therefore as this BP also mentions, it will basically require changing a parameter to use ml2 as the core plugin or anything else. If it still makes sense to add the new set of playbooks to rpc_extras, I can restructure this BP.'}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:02:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:04:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

- gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/26/184726/6/check/gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs/438357e//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 32s'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-05-31 23:45:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-2

@Javeria,

Thank you very much for submitting this spec and doing the work you have on modularizing the neutron roles such that they will support additional drivers/capabilities. That work is very much appreciated and progress the OSAD project immensely as we look to support more and more services / features. With that said, after much deliberation I have decided that the PLUMgrid specific roles will not be allowed into the stack due to our desire to keep OSAD a pure OpenStack/open source deployment system. I love the fact that the modular neutron plugin has been setup within the Juno branch and enables neutron to consume additional out of tree network providers IE PLUMgrid. I do like the network model that PLUMgrid has created and I believe that the IOvisor is the future to full stack integration for networking and more. Furthermore, as a technologist I will be pushing deployers PLUMgrid’s way for future larger deployments that outgrow the LinuxBridge agent capabilities. However those vendor specific roles will need to be maintained in a repository outside of OSAD and the general OpenStack/StackForge namespaces. While there are plenty of projects within OpenStack that allow vendor specific contributions we do not want to be one of them as we’re choosing the upstream/"BigTent" approach to all deployments for overall maintainability and stability. 

If it were I creating these roles, I would look at getting them into public github and linking with upstream Ansible Galaxy. With the roles in Ansible Galaxy OSAD and other Ansible projects would be able to consume the roles as external resources. OSAD already has the capability to consume external resources by simply listing the external roles within the `ansible-role-requirements.yml` file which would allow deployers to enable PLUMgrid services and capabilities. 

As I stated before we appreciate the work that you’ve put into this thus far and would love to work with you on getting the roles upstreamed for greater Ansible consumption and we hope you understand the project's position. Assuming you continue with the development of the PLUMgrid Ansible roles we, the OpenStack-Ansible community, would love to see them come to fruition so if you have questions on role development, best practices, or anything else please don't hesitate to ping us.'}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-06-01 21:45:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thank you Kevin for your review and detailed feedback. We understand your point of view completely, and keeping the OSAD goals in mind, it does make sense to add external roles to a public community such as Ansible Galaxy. To that end, we are still very much interested in supporting OSAD, and therefore our team will now pursue upstreaming the PLUMgrid Ansible roles to Ansible Galaxy. However, I believe Juno does not provide the capability of consuming external roles. How do you propose we integrate with that branch? 

Since the PLUMgrid plugin itself is open source, would OSAD be open adding it as an option to the modularized neutron plays? That is, add a plumgrid entry to the 'neutron_plugins' dictionary, that can be chosen and will lead to installing the neutron-plugin-plumgrid package that can be had from Ubuntu repos."}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-06-02 21:32:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 15526, 'date': '2015-06-02 21:34:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Have amended the spec to now only cover adding PLUMgrid as a core plugin option in neutron config. The rest of the PLUMgrid installation will be kept externally.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-02 21:38:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

I'm happy with the changes made. It's more explicit that the changes are to add support for configuring the additional driver and not to deploy the back-end framework for it."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-06-08 07:51:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Add PLUMgrid Neutron Plugin to neutron playbooks

This spec summarizes the requirements for inserting
PLUMgrid as a plugin option to the neutron playbooks.

Patch 3/4: added some more clarification on changes required

Patch 7: BP now only deals with adding PLUMgrid plugin as a core
         neutron plugin option

Implements blueprint: add-plumgrid-neutron-plugin

Change-Id: Id57dc5f7e39a358be558aca0797972b3a82fc9da
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Check domain's enabled attribute strictly

Current test_domains checks domain's enabled attribute after converting
it to string because maybe that is for XML format. However, now Tempest
doesn't test XML format and the response of "create domain" is checked
as True instead of converting it to string.
This patch removes these conversions for checking boolean attribute.

Change-Id: I958de1e13b0169b03b56e4db1872d5ccf4e8904e

commit_message:
Rearrange static dir layout

- moved everything from js dir to the top
- renamed static/libs to static/vendor
- renamed static/css to static/styles; styles.less to main.less
- removed obsolete entries from config.js

Change-Id: Ic20c0604f844d80092f65a7be7be4710e1a50928

commit_message:
Fix condition of Swift SLO API tests run

Swift Static Large Object API tests get run even if not set slo in
[object-storage-feature-enabled] of tempest.conf.
So it always fails unless Swift's slo is enabled.

This change makes the test run only when set slo in tempest.conf.

Change-Id: I9f256e0395fd606fd1cf64d2bffd5c00802c9cf4
Closes-Bug: 1458768

commit_message:
Added dangling mock detection to 'guestagent'

Ensured that no dangling mocks exist by having each test class extend
trove_testtools.TestCase

Ran 'tox -epy27' and fixed any detected problems.

Change-Id: Ib43b86f74036a71c65bd2b1bd7b0905a1d8520b7
Partial-Bug: 1448273

commit_message:
Prepare ELK TOSCA Template for Translation into HOT

Make necessary modifications to the ELK template and the scripts
for proper deployment of the translated HOT template.

Partially Implements: blueprint translate-tosca-monitoring-usecase

commit_message:
Fix installation package name

Installation of heat-translator from debian package fails
when the package name was 'translator'.
Changing it to 'heat-translator' so package import didn't throw
errors.

Closes-Bug: #1458486
Change-Id: I83c0469e78bc99d3a016e3eb41b836ce3c06f2f9

db_upgrade and db_downgrade method were not using the argument repo_path,
rather they were passing explicitly None for this argument to called methods
db_api.db_upgrade & db_api.db_downgrade, respectively.

Change-Id: Idaa9a1953a4eef18a4f676d9f82877fd9bc70b10
Closes-Bug: #1462450
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes db_upgrade and db_downgrade methods

db_upgrade and db_downgrade method were not using the argument repo_path,
rather they were passing explicitly None for this argument to called methods
db_api.db_upgrade & db_api.db_downgrade, respectively.

Change-Id: Idaa9a1953a4eef18a4f676d9f82877fd9bc70b10
Closes-Bug: #1462450

[{'created': '2015-05-27 23:56:03.000000000', 'message': 'Remove unnecessary string conversions for status reports

Status.text is already a string or a unicode object. That is because
text is of type sa.Text() in database, and api serializes it as such.

Unnecessary conversion to str prevented unicode statuses from displaying
correctly in dashboard (although deployment continued normally).

This change allows murano dashboard to display unicode statuses. We ♥

'}]
commit_message:
Remove unnecessary string conversions for status reports

Status.text is already a string or a unicode object. That is because
text is of type sa.Text() in database, and api serializes it as such.

Unnecessary conversion to str prevented unicode statuses from displaying
correctly in dashboard (although deployment continued normally).

This change allows murano dashboard to display unicode statuses. We ♥
unicode.

Change-Id: Ic02d2d55c13a555fd878f50b83f32a4f36a6904f

commit_message:
Remove the sqlite entry point

This entry point existed for backwards compatibility. It's not needed
anymore, make ppl move to sqlalchemy if needed.

Change-Id: I2715961bae9473b55a68af6d9441d83ccdf85735

commit_message:
Remove messages and claims from sql code

Remove data modules from the sqlalchemy package since we don't support
them anymore.

Closes-bug: #1461962

commit_message:
Remove `marconi-server`

The marconi-server entry point was kept for backwards compatibility. It
should be safe to remove it now.

Change-Id: I912e57cb4e72e185e00067c950d6dfc7fc6dd9b9

commit_message:
Deprecate v1

This patch marks v1 as deprecated. It'll be removed in the next cycle
and we won't  be fixing things for it anymore. This change should be
reflected in the client library as well.

In this patch, devstack has been switched to use v2 directly, which is
the current developed/maintained version.

APIImpact

Change-Id: I2f32828835b3329b37bf7bac04024c46c161054a

can be resized at most to 1324 GB which might be too small given
the sizes of the modern hard drives. Make sure the image can be resized
to 8TB.

The gory details: ext4 reserves some blocks for filesystem metadata
(block group descriptors) which are used for growing the filesystem.
The number of reserved blocks determines how large the filesystem can
possilby grow. For smaller filesystems too few blocks gets reserved.
As a work around use a slightly bigger initial filesystem so it can
be expanded up to 8 TB.

TBs produces very suboptimal metadata layout and incurs substantial
performance degradation (15 -- 25%). Also resizing takes much longer
than unpacking a tarball (with the same content). So a proper fix is
rewriting IBP code to use a better backup/restore mechanism (which
is essentially what IBP does).

commit_message:
image/centos: generate an image resizable to common HD sizes

At the moment the (CentOS) root filesystem image shipped with the ISO
can be resized at most to 1324 GB which might be too small given
the sizes of the modern hard drives. Make sure the image can be resized
to 8TB.

The gory details: ext4 reserves some blocks for filesystem metadata
(block group descriptors) which are used for growing the filesystem.
The number of reserved blocks determines how large the filesystem can
possilby grow. For smaller filesystems too few blocks gets reserved.
As a work around use a slightly bigger initial filesystem so it can
be expanded up to 8 TB.

It should be noted that expanding a few GB sized filesystem to several
TBs produces very suboptimal metadata layout and incurs substantial
performance degradation (15 -- 25%). Also resizing takes much longer
than unpacking a tarball (with the same content). So a proper fix is
rewriting IBP code to use a better backup/restore mechanism (which
is essentially what IBP does).

Related-Bug: #1459665
Change-Id: I07f2233d0db68be1c72307f85a99eddaf54c9346

commit_message:
Refactor PureISCSIDriver into base and iSCSI classes.

This adds in a new class called PureBaseVolumeDriver that contains
all of the generic shared methods that utilize the management REST API.

The PureISCSIDriver now inherits from the base driver and implements
the functionality required for iSCSI hosts/initiators.

As part of this we’ve cleaned up some of the logging where it would
previously have hard coded the drivers class name in it, and moved some
static non-class helper methods into the base class.

These changes will ease future work to add additional drivers or split
them into separate files.

Implements: blueprint pure-base-driver
Change-Id: Iaf3979e5cccc150d09ca00daa3d9c3471f9795a0

commit_message:
Fixes DiskInfoPollster AttributeError exception

If a NotImplementedError exception is raised while getting samples through
a DiskInfoPollster, another exception occurs, as it tries to access an
attribute that does not exist.

Replaces the usage of manager.inspector with self.inspector.

Change-Id: Ie1bb6eaffc0b2671f8fefb4771dbd2191eb5cf5f
Closes-Bug: #1460207
(cherry picked from commit b8b90ac0fd7fcf028cae5be24bd2551c116d80f8)

commit_message:
Add security group check when boot with port

When create a vm with specified security group and ports,the security
group is invalid.Because ports have their own security group.Perhaps users
will be confused with this situation.They input security group
parameter,but it doesn't work.

This patch add security group check in api and log out a warning.

Change-Id: If956731b2b82360f69bced78b05a473f9d5b86c9
Closes-bug:#1462393

commit_message:
Add a decorator for deprecating keyword parameters

This simple decorator, when applied to a method accepting keyword
parameters will allow for emitting warnings if deprecated
parameters are explicitly passed to the method.

Related-Bug #1449462

Change-Id: Ia3ea5e7167c38630d94201fe946d7fb32ead8069

commit_message:
Added more unit-tests to improve code coverage

Following files were too low on code coverage,
so the coverage has been enhanced with addition of more unit-tests.
- troveclient/client.py
- troveclient/v1/shell.py

The methodology to test shell has been motivated from the
one used by python-novaclient to test novaclient/v2/shell.py

Change-Id: Ib040b69d31956231f1f6de57775d613fa8fdda7f

Diane - thanks for adding this documentation.  Regarding the "3.4" issue, two things:

- When the spec says it "requires 3.4", what it really means is that it requires a keystone server running at least 3.4 of the API
- The original version of OS-INHERIT came well before 3.4, but was extended in 3.4 to allow inheritance from projects (the original only allowed inheritance from domains). commit_message:
Improve local.conf sample for devstack

The local.conf sample file is meant to minimize configurations required to run
devstack with midonet as the neutron plugin.  In this patch the following
entries are added:

 * Enable Horizon since it's needed in most dev scenarios
 * Add default password for the services

Also, rename the file to local.conf.sample

Change-Id: Idae8b03dd51bebafb25da2d09d22a807c358de63
Implements: MNP-137

commit_message:
Do not require scheduling attributes in ramdisk

Discovery data might be used for other things as well, like ready-state
orchestration.

Change-Id: Ifc9089ea6af634e2b0ab6b771d156d346bf43383

commit_message:
Set the supported extensions in __init__

Instead of setting the supported extension aliases when the plugin class
is loaded, do so when the plugin object is created.

Without this patch, the unit tests for extra extensions required
unnecessary extra care with regards to the timing of the plugin module
import and the configuration overrides.

More concretely, in the unit tests, the configuration overrides happen
in the test setup, and that's when the extra extensions get registered.
However, since the Neutron plugin class accesses the
supported_extension_aliases of the MidoNet mixin class statically, as
soon as the plugin module loads (i.e. imported), the supported aliases
get set before the configurations could be modified.

Change-Id: I455474dd89c1a42805a5b6b68a4d5514161ad40f
Fixes: MNP-135

commit_message:
Fix Rally scenario names for Manila jobs

Currently set names for Rally scenarios will be renamed to be Rally-wide
compatible. So, rename them here to be able to rename them in appropriate
Rally commits too.

commit_message:
Fix for availability_zone in instances table

if instance is booted without --availability_zone
param and no default_schedule_zone conf set
instance.availability_zone field is set to NULL in
db. Fix this by updating AZ during instance boot
after scheduling step

Related-bug: #1451921
Change-Id: I47d02689f38bb486eb5cd6ace169744f95f231a3

is set for it(availability_zone=NULL) in db. If then make
attempt to live-migrate this instance scheduler could provide
wrong destination host as no az info is provided.

it is manually calculated, for current instance host.

commit_message:
Fix availability zone check before live-migration

if instance is booted without az provided, no az info
is set for it(availability_zone=NULL) in db. If then make
attempt to live-migrate this instance scheduler could provide
wrong destination host as no az info is provided.
Added check in scheduler. If no az in request_spec is provided,
it is manually calculated, for current instance host.

Closes-bug: #1451921

Change-Id: I70c9f736521e6835f7d5bb96b31ebd876a4c9378

commit_message:
Refactor client code to be pluginized

Instead of having functions that generate the various plugins with no shared sessions between them we make use of a ClientManager object that generates the various clients on demand using a shared keystone session that handles the auth / reauth.

Change-Id: Ib532956f0d18e7ee9661b2abe649e260dba23578

commit_message:
Revise webhook-create support in client

This patch revised the client-side support to webhook creation. We now
save users from manually input 'obj_type' which makes little to no sense
to them. This is done by providing three separate arguments for users to
choose from.

Change-Id: I8f339af3007f5272f1259a933dd1ea1d8632b2db

commit_message:
Refactor Huawei Volume driver

This blueprint is an attempt to refactor the Huawei volume driver in liberty.
We will add a base dirver to implement the basic functions that the Cinder driver required.
The sub-class will inherit the base driver according to different storages.
the following diragram shows the structure of the newest Huawei volume driver

        +---------------+ +------------------+ +--------------------+
        | ISCSIDriver | | HuaweiBaseDriver | | FibreChannelDriver |
        +---------+-----+ +----+-------------+ +----+-----------+----+
                  | | | |
                  | | |__________ |
                  | | | |
              +---+--------------------+ +---+--------------------+
              | Huawei18000ISCSIDriver | | Huawei18000FCDriver |
              +-------------+----------+ +-------------+----------+

Change-Id: I73a851034fea59483622c2997d2175d5661ef6cf
Implements: bp/refactor-huawei-volume-driver

commit_message:
Remove project association before removing endpoint group

Since `project_endpoint_group` has a foreign key reference with `endpoint_group`
thus, if we want to remove endpoint_group we need to remove associated
`project_endpoint_group` at first.

The testcase provided can pass even without code changing only beacuse SQLITE
didn't enforce foreign key constraint by default, so endpoint group with project
association can be deleted (needn't delete project association at first)
successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1443765
bp ondelete-cascade

Change-Id: Id685948373ffb37467f336172a085b91c982cbc7
(cherry picked from commit 4b7758c2d633d81411371134e008260baac6c05c)

commit_message:
Add deprecation warning for ResourceDefinition

Docstring of class ResourceDefinition tells, that backward compatible
methods should be deprecated in favor of using methods in
ResourceDefinitionCore, but there is no any warning message about it.

This patch adds deprecation warnings.
Aslo related tests were changed to check, that deprecation warning is
really raised.

Change-Id: Ie881a1bdb88f4bcb1c03c037bcedf2a328d5d41c

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary dependencies from KerberosDomain

KerberosDomain doesn't use assignment_api or identity_api directly
and these are provided by the base class.

Change-Id: Ia27ddfc9bcb1d5d41b3a126f2c6027813a44fb1f

[{'created': '2015-06-04 12:15:23.000000000', 'message': 'Add size check when boot with blank in volume

Currently when boot with bdm like:source=blank,dest=volume without
size.The vm will be error with No valid host was found.

So we should check size information in api side.

Change-Id: I82c36f92ed2f3e3ff9ef5b29ef3891f94b002e8d
Closes-bug:#1461891
'}]
commit_message:
Add size check when boot with blank in volume

Currently when boot with bdm like:source=blank,dest=volume without
size.The vm will be error with No valid host was found.

So we should check size information in api side.

Change-Id: I82c36f92ed2f3e3ff9ef5b29ef3891f94b002e8d
Closes-bug:#1461891

commit_message:
Do not create and destroy Sahara templates if exists

Validation error in Sahara is occurred during scaling cluster (add
one more controller), when some Sahara template in use. So, do not
destroy Sahara templates.

Also, do not recreate template if exists.

Change-Id: I629046b70d93d3c040bc104270254f11a07c91a3
Closes-bug: #1462422

commit_message:
Ensure ext-net is defined as a flat network

If not defined as flat, the ext-net will be created as either gre,
vxlan or vlan depending on network_type set for datacentre.

Change-Id: Ieb1a9842410ecf4e89af075a4190c3a28036df9c

commit_message:
Update mongodb implementation to reflect master

Two PR have been merged upstream that let use improve our current
implementation :

  * service_manage[1]
  * conn string has namevar[2]

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-mongodb/pull/198
[2] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-mongodb/pull/200

Change-Id: Ia2247348a9e0292b5fcbc65ea1e41e6bc7c477fa

commit_message:
Move description of how to boot instance with ISO to user-guide

The description of how to boot instance with ISO should be in user-guide
instead of config-ref
(doc/config-reference/image-service/section_image-service-ISO-support.xml).
Related to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177691/.

Change-Id: I2ac2098474851cdbad5ef07ed6f78af12dafd243
Closes-Bug:#1450419

subject: Add module implementing DN, RDN & AVA objects to improve DN handling
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 4, 'name': 'Dolph Mathews', 'email': 'dolph.mathews@gmail.com', 'username': 'dolph'}, {'_account_id': 2218, 'name': 'Adam Young', 'email': 'adam@younglogic.com', 'username': 'ayoung'}, {'_account_id': 2903, 'name': 'Morgan Fainberg', 'email': 'morgan.fainberg@gmail.com', 'username': 'mdrnstm'}, {'_account_id': 7191, 'name': 'Jamie Lennox', 'email': 'jamielennox@gmail.com', 'username': 'jamielennox'}, {'_account_id': 7725, 'name': 'David Stanek', 'email': 'dstanek@dstanek.com', 'username': 'dstanek'}, {'_account_id': 8116, 'name': 'John Dennis', 'email': 'jdennis@redhat.com', 'username': 'jdennis'}, {'_account_id': 9098, 'name': 'Nathan Kinder', 'email': 'nkinder@redhat.com', 'username': 'nkinder'}, {'_account_id': 9751, 'name': 'IBM DB2 CI', 'email': 'scecd@cn.ibm.com', 'username': 'ibmdb2', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2014-05-23 22:02:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2014-05-23 22:04:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

This is a libary that implements DN, RDN and AVA objects. It was born
out the need for a more robust solution to using DN's in the IPA
project. IPA makes extremely heavy use of LDAP, as a consequence we
were always operating on Distinguished Names (DN). Initially we always
expressed DN's as strings. But it quickly became apparent that was the
source of many problems, this was especially true when DN's were
composed from user input where escaping and internationalization had
to be properly handled. Also we discovered programmers were writing
the similar (local) code over and over to try and manipulate DN's and
repeatedly making the same mistakes. It was time for a library, it was
time for a smart object to hide the complexity and simplify code and
time for greater robustness.

This module has been in use in IPA for several years now, so far no
problems have been discovered. There is a matching unit test.

There is extensive module and class level documentation in dn.py,
please read it.

The module is based on the str2dn() and dn2str() functions in the
python-ldap dn library. We believe this module should be part of
python-ldap and we're exploring that.

There is one known issue, the way DN objects produce their string
representation will only work correctly in Python2. This is a
consequence of how string handling has changed in Python3 in addition
to python-ldap's string handling behavior in Python2. At the moment
python-ldap is not available for Python3. At some point the Python3
issues need to be addressed, but given there isn't even a version of
python-ldap for Python3 yet the the 2 to 3 conversion problem can be
deferred."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-23 22:04:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add module implementing DN, RDN & AVA objects to improve DN handling

LDAP DN's can be difficult to operate on easily and correctly,
encapsule all the special logic inside a class which knows how to
operate on Distinguished Names and their components.

Extensive documentation is in dn.py and a unit test is provided.

Change-Id: Ibf47904e349a7ea81931af58963eb4e5406324d8

commit_message:
Change hardcoded dates in test to relative ones

test_dates_filtering from test_oswl_stats_to_csv.py mixed dates
hardcoded into test and current date in csv_exporter. Test now uses
current date as a base.

Change-Id: Ic57444181b02dbbb39c938ea709f3d4593da0e85
Closes-Bug: #1460590

Port ProphetStor driver to use ABCMeta driver model

Use new ABCMeta driver model for ProphetStor driver.

Change-Id: Ic8ecbecb661971a4535a6899b0d104ef5bdf0011
Implements: blueprint abc-driver-update

commit_message:
Use a single method to remove an address with its conntrack state

I just noticed a pattern and I thought I'd throw this up for
discussion.  It has occurred to me that this addition sort of breaks
the ip_lib paradigm of wrapping ip commands without any additional
useful abstraction.  Any better ideas?

Change-Id: Ibd34bf4a721c153aca916e294e58adb4a28379e4

commit_message:
Add action parameter to attach & detach mothods of policy

This patch added action input parameter for attach & detach
methods of policy module since this param is necessary for performing
action control during policy attaching/detaching progress. Meanwhile,
context input parameter is removed since it can be got from
action.context.

Change-Id: Icb065f434f29ccb906fc86f4e1543d82ee1a1bdf

[{'created': '2015-05-12 17:54:29.000000000', 'message': 'Dell: Added verify cert option for REST calls

If one goes through the trouble to create a cert and
install it on the Dell Data Collector and on the cinder
node then we can enable certificate verification on the
request calls to the Dell REST API.

This simply makes dell_sc_verify_cert a cinder.conf option
for a Dell backend and directly uses that as the verify
option on the REST requests.  Default is False.

Change-Id: I22348d5e0b55d56f44f1fc4f0c830790a6670494
Closes-bug: 1452919

commit_message:
Dell: Added verify cert option for REST calls

If one goes through the trouble to create a cert and
install it on the Dell Data Collector and on the cinder
node then we can enable certificate verification on the
request calls to the Dell REST API.

This simply makes dell_sc_verify_cert a cinder.conf option
for a Dell backend and directly uses that as the verify
option on the REST requests.  Default is False.

The update_migrated_volume function arrived via a rebase
and had a merge issue that was fixed.  Specifically the
dell_sc_ssn value is no longer part of the api.find_sc
call.

Spelling error also corrected in a LOG message.

SecImpact

Change-Id: I22348d5e0b55d56f44f1fc4f0c830790a6670494
Implements: blueprint dell-sc-add-verify-cert

commit_message:
Revert "Add VIF_DELETED notification event to Nova"

We need to wait until the nova support is added in
I998b6bb80cc0a81d665b61b8c4a424d7219c666f. Otherwise
this generates a ton of error messages in the nova api
log as well as on the neutron side.

This reverts commit 0ace88fd4a75ff213dc36fd16c1f8e7080ab7d6d.

Change-Id: I129c4e4c05cf07d45032fec6f57e0cc17a5a82af
Closes-Bug: #1461391

commit_message:
Remove full stack log noise

"neutron-server isn't up yet" logs are useless because if
you time out when waiting for the server to start that information
will be in the trace. When you don't time out, the log is just spam.

Same reasoning for the "There are %d agents running!" log.

Also made the agents_count parameter mandatory for the
wait_until_env_is_up method because having a default of 0, or any
other default makes no sense. There's no reason to ever call that
method without specifying the agents_count. This method used
to be used with agents_count == 0 by the server to make sure
its up (And responding to REST calls), but the Neutron server
fixture now uses server_is_live method (Which calls list_networks)
instead.

Change-Id: Ifd6abd04ddaacc9976cb2a75269443f870b47c5b

Add support for driver method 'instance_exists()'

commit_message:
Put six at the top of requirements.txt

Six is often a dependency of other packages, if it is lower down than
such a package, whatever version constraints we have may not be
honoured.

In particular
python-glanceclient->PyOpenSSL->cryptography->setup_requires('six')
was triggering this in Ironic.

Change-Id: I0aa00c604fb2bb2f94cc76cc0ac07855cb414ffd

commit_message:
Lock tox below 2.0 to allow project fixups.

Tox 2.0 introduces more isolation from environment variables but many
of our testing regimes depend on those variables to work. Lock our use
below 2.0 until thats fixed.

Change-Id: I85634708a564b7c2ebc4fe2055a9e372cbf3ea3b

commit_message:
Revert "Add dependency for FIP if used network in port"

This patch reverts I4fb108c46c950e588d630d2dcef925ce405b4e34,
because in the fix tried to use stack domain user to access
neutron network API, but stack domain user doesn't has the
permission.

Closes-Bug: #1442121

commit_message:
VMware: remove unused spawn power_on parameter

The spawn method does not have a power_on option according to the
driver interface. The VM should always be powered on after creation.
This parameter is also never used.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I6bd81f8526a41313553e26f490eaac30ea0e6f40

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-05 17:39:35.000000000', 'message': 'Fix cloud-init Python syntax for Python < 2.6

The loguserdata.py file gets uploaded to the servers created by Heat to run
under cloud-init. Since the default versions of Python installed on the
user's server may be very old (e.g. RHEL 5 defaults to Python 2.4), avoid
using the octal syntax introduced for Python 3.0 and backported only as far
as Python 2.6. (Also avoid the old syntax, which will break on Python 3.x.)

Also remove use of the "with" statement from loguserdata.py and
part-handler.py. This statement is only available from Python 2.6 on (or in
Python 2.5 via "from __future__ import with_statement").

Finally, remove use of the "except ExceptionType as value" syntax for
catching exceptions. Again, this was only backported to Python 2.6.

Change-Id: I89e86d00993d51e2514b1e589503c6d966909403
Partial-Bug: #1375864
(cherry picked from commit 95ec13c5725ccc19dfe910fe83eb9bc6799d482e)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix cloud-init Python syntax for Python < 2.6

The loguserdata.py file gets uploaded to the servers created by Heat to run
under cloud-init. Since the default versions of Python installed on the
user's server may be very old (e.g. RHEL 5 defaults to Python 2.4), avoid
using the octal syntax introduced for Python 3.0 and backported only as far
as Python 2.6. (Also avoid the old syntax, which will break on Python 3.x.)

Also remove use of the "with" statement from loguserdata.py and
part-handler.py. This statement is only available from Python 2.6 on (or in
Python 2.5 via "from __future__ import with_statement").

Finally, remove use of the "except ExceptionType as value" syntax for
catching exceptions. Again, this was only backported to Python 2.6.

Change-Id: I89e86d00993d51e2514b1e589503c6d966909403
Partial-Bug: #1375864
(cherry picked from commit 95ec13c5725ccc19dfe910fe83eb9bc6799d482e)

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I501dc28a8f883e44dedb915dc98b283ea4e9fb4f

commit_message:
Create bridges in ovsdb monitor functional tests

The test waits inside for output from 'ovsdb-client monitor Bridge'
command but the command makes output only if there is a bridge present
in ovsdb. This patch adds an OVSBridgeFixture to setup so every test
case has a bridge for sure.

Change-Id: I40e1c99ec956c92fa1c7763eb98f7f2ce6fcd226
Closes-Bug: 1447191
(cherry picked from commit aa57c364defec8519bbed06fbce5aae4b23f147f)

commit_message:
Refactor mlnx mechanism driver to support infiniband only

The old mlnx mechanism driver was used for SR-IOV with Ethernet
and infiniband support but the PCI allocation wasn't done by nova.
Juno introduced sriovnicswitch mechanism driver for SR-IOV with
Ethernet support. Mellanox recommends on using it.
The updated mlnx mechanism driver supports SR-IOV infiniband.

* support only port vnic_type 'direct'
* update vif_type name to ib_hostdev (the ib_hostdev is generic vif_type
  for SR-IOV infiniband see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/187052/)

Closes-Bug: #1460430
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia822b492afdfeb1aecf373d5a8cdb72174512884

commit_message:
Adds a MAINTAINERS file

Adds a MAINTAINERS file listing contacts for subsystems to direct new
contributors to individuals that can answer questions on IRC or email.

Change-Id: Id71f5451dc17f374feff1a3bdb35fb9ec42f0fa1
Depends-On: Ia27881a34ff99cad34c84764d2bf8a6cdf77af9c

'}]
commit_message:
Add more API tests for port-security extension:

Test create port with specific value of port_security_enabled
Test create secure port with security_group attached
Test update port with port_security_enabled True\False
and with or without security groups
Test deleting port with port_security_enabled

Change-Id: Id71f5451dc17f374feff1a3bdb35fb9ec42f0fa1
Depends-On: Ia27881a34ff99cad34c84764d2bf8a6cdf77af9c
Depends-On: Ie0ec090e8fdce7dbdbce14ef47f38e8e57f262d4

commit_message:
Experimental job for Nova API services under Apache2

Nova has been updated here:
Idd7d3d1b3cc5770cdecea7afe6db3c89d5b2c0d0

Devstack has been updated here:
I9fc0c601db2776d3e9084be84065e728e3f5d414

So now we need a job to make sure we don't break
the support we added in nova and devstack

Change-Id: I5806a98e82e6babb2b6ab534fa0e457f98f3cf31

commit_message:
Rename directory with rally jobs files.

Directory `rally-scenarios' is renamed to `rally-jobs'.
New name is required by Rally documentation, old name
`rally-scenarios' is deprecated.

Reference:
  https://rally.readthedocs.org/en/latest/gates.html

Change-Id: Iee24ebc4c6cbfb8aa91ab2bb284ac44cc9598c0c

commit_message:
Enforce usage of project scoped token

In order for functionality to remain intact (ie disallow people to create / do
actions in designate that ends up with a "None" tenant_id as the owner in the
db) we need to enforce the use of a project scoped token for now.

Closes-Bug: #1460187

Change-Id: I8a64fe4938b3b9b0ade9fe210e4da0d19ad1c23f
(cherry picked from commit ae235cba3c5bda5d1da6816135400107660a2794)

commit_message:
Refactor: use __getitem__ when the key will exists

In this case we check to see if the key exists already so we know it
will be there.

Change-Id: I894e8416206945915c838ce72707981c9dee9aca

commit_message:
Refactor: create the lookup object once

The lookup for JSON content types is now a module level set instead of
creating a new tuple when render_response is called.

Change-Id: I3ee7a33ac765ec221dda2388eeb168a0d5a88d13

[{'created': '2015-05-11 20:53:24.000000000', 'message': "Fix ubuntu vagrant box nodesets

Without this patch, the nodesets incorrectly define a vagrantcloud vm
to install, resulting in the following error:

 > The box you're adding has a name different from the name you
 > requested.

This patch uses the trusty vagrant nodeset from the puppetlabs-apache
module and updates the default nodeset as well. Fill do the same for
the centos nodeset in a separate patch after RedHat tests are
implemented.

Change-Id: Iffac76b48d496d93b9cb63323ac103619319de47
"}]
commit_message:
Fix ubuntu vagrant box nodesets

Without this patch, the nodesets incorrectly define a vagrantcloud vm
to install, resulting in the following error:

 > The box you're adding has a name different from the name you
 > requested.

This patch uses the trusty vagrant nodeset from the puppetlabs-apache
module and updates the default nodeset as well. Fill do the same for
the centos nodeset in a separate patch after RedHat tests are
implemented.

Change-Id: Iffac76b48d496d93b9cb63323ac103619319de47

Using the variable reference also breaks rspec-puppet

to fully resolve all the dependencies.

Change-Id: Ica4bd1d3336d59d66d8da01194bba825d958943a
"}]
commit_message:
rather use the alias and keep references consistent

Using the variable reference also breaks rspec-puppet
tests with compile.with_all_deps as it won't be able
to fully resolve all the dependencies.

Change-Id: Ica4bd1d3336d59d66d8da01194bba825d958943a

commit_message:
NetApp: use $name for configuration group name

For NetApp backends, set the name of the backend configuration
group in cinder.conf to the title of the defined type for the
backend (rather than using 'volume_backend_name'). This allows
to support multiple backend configuration groups to use the same
volume_backend_name.

Change-Id: Ic47fd0036e1ba3e23a35286b4e8faee93edc8de4

commit_message:
Add test_port_list_filter_by_ip test

This will create a network, subnet and two ports specifying
an ip address for each port, and then will list the port
filtering by ip address, to check if the returned port
is the same that were created (same port id, ip address
and network id)

Change-Id: I354a3a7edeccf13779219c8570c72acfca7173c9

commit_message:
Fix deprecated LDAP config options

In Juno, the tenant_* LDAP related options are deprecated in favor of
project_*. See Table 7.38 here:
http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/keystone-conf-changes-juno.html

Change-Id: I6da58559478d92df8facab1bf8191fdb2b44259b
(cherry picked from commit f8e3ed7fdd155383ab2fe461349aaa9095ed80a2)

commit_message:
Split slow rally job to several small ones

Job gate-rally-dsvm-rally does check rally scenarios for all openstack
services. This takes almost one hour.

Here we move heat, cinder and nova scenarios to separate jobs. So we
will have 5 jobs instead of 2.

Change-Id: I6fbae8240311540588b13adbadc4338067d6c618

The other packages appear to already have this, but heat-common isn't
triggering a db sync, and at least on Ubuntu, if this package is
upgraded first, all the others get pulled in also.  When that happens,

Change-Id: I454220ee6c501c416b60564fd3b1f00fdecfd296
"}]
commit_message:
Run db_sync when heat-common is upgraded

The other packages appear to already have this, but heat-common isn't
triggering a db sync, and at least on Ubuntu, if this package is
upgraded first, all the others get pulled in also.  When that happens,
Puppet doesn't trigger a notification for the other packages and the db
sync is never run.

Change-Id: I454220ee6c501c416b60564fd3b1f00fdecfd296

commit_message:
The Tenant subnet dic and the Routes were pointing to the same Subnet
Object, that caused problems and sync issues
Modify the subnets dic in the router class to be a list of the subnet
ids connected to this router.
Accessing the object is from the Tenant main subnets dic

Change-Id: I193b201132f5a7d524833ba03804886b48967745

commit_message:
Enforce usage of project scoped token

In order for functionality to remain intact (ie disallow people to create / do
actions in designate that ends up with a "None" tenant_id as the owner in the
db) we need to enforce the use of a project scoped token for now.

Closes-Bug: #1460187

Change-Id: I8a64fe4938b3b9b0ade9fe210e4da0d19ad1c23f

commit_message:
Set owner of Q_VPN_CONF_FILE file to STACK_USER user

Functional tests need to have access to configuration files.
Since the tests are started under 'stack' user
(sudo -H -u stack tox -e dsvm-functional) it would be better
to change owner of the Q_VPN_CONF_FILE file to STACK_USER.

Change-Id: I1ca677a805872726667df641255201cdd4cf4037

commit_message:
Reenable test_list_servers_filtered_by_ip_regex

It seems that bug #1182883 which has been the reason to skip
test_list_servers_filtered_by_ip_regex has been resolved for some time.
So we reenable this test and only skip the ip6 part that is still
pending on #1450859.

Change-Id: I4e926496fe317daee3be3d8c62c90723a04a7e23

commit_message:
JSCS cleanup - Angular framework widgets (partial)

We need to do cleanup before we can enable JSCS globally
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185725/).

Widgets included: action-list, charts, help-panel, magic-search,
metadata-display, metadata-tree.

Change-Id: I3b2f105946d4920c866bc60d0c4e970ef2994c33
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

commit_message:
Have conductors be disconnected from builder helper methods

Instead of having the methods that are used to create a engine,
flow detail or listener list be tightly bound to a conductor
create a helper object that contains just these strategies and
can be passed into conductor instances.

This reduces the conductor __init__ arguments and allows for these
types of strategies to be customized more easily (without having
to subclass).

This is a backwards incompatible change for users directly interacting
with the conductor classes (for example for those that are subclassing
them); but for those that are using the conductor fetch() entrypoint
this should be a compatible change that continues working as it previously
was.

Change-Id: I46e5d01af30b05be7deb4f5df1fd8218e02585ec

commit_message:
Return provider_id in 3PAR volume model update

The provider_id field was added in
commit: 9f34d34d0ab92400223e3cc87285d0d4fbdf21f9
This patch adds provider_id to the returned model
update and uses it to provide the internal 3PAR
volume name mapping.

Change-Id: I00f1a159c036f9058305c278539a77b2df87f837

builddoc: allow to use fnmatch-style exclusion for autodoc

autodoc genereation.

commit_message:
Add entrypoints for option discovery

oslo-config-generator relies on entrypoints listed
in setup.cfg to add options to the generated sample conf
files in different projects. So expose options avaliable in
oslo.service using the following entrypoints:

* oslo.service.periodic_task
* oslo.service.service
* oslo.service.sslutils

The following commands can be used to generate sample conf:
tox -evenv -- oslo-config-generator --namespace oslo.service.periodic_task
tox -evenv -- oslo-config-generator --namespace oslo.service.service
tox -evenv -- oslo-config-generator --namespace oslo.service.sslutils

bp graduate-oslo-service
Change-Id: I61372047b70341e3536db21aa3f1bd9d99c08185

[{'created': '2015-06-05 09:25:39.000000000', 'message': 'Introduce abstract base class for services

Service object that is passed to any launcher must implement
the following methods:
    * start
    * stop
    * wait
    * reset

Introducing abstract base class from which all openstack
services that use common.service code can subclass guarantees it.

commit_message:
Introduce abstract base class for services

Service object that is passed to any launcher must implement
the following methods:
    * start
    * stop
    * wait
    * reset

Introducing abstract base class from which all openstack
services that use common.service code can subclass guarantees it.

Added documentation for launcher classes in service.py

Change-Id: I79b38a354dd85f58a7c16b34661bff02d9170a9f
Closes-Bug: #1447965

More explicit data_files install location docs

Make it obvious to the reader that data_files installation target
location translates to the actual system-wide root filesystem tree
when installed with sufficient permissions to do so.

commit_message:
Fix test case to be runnable with gnupg 2.1

In gnupg 2.1 %no-ask-passphrase is a no-op.  As a result gpg attempts to
prompt for a passphrase and as the shell is not interactive it fails.

To allow gnupg 2.1 to create passphrase-less keys we enable two options
new to gnupg 2.1.

%no-protection
%transient-key

Change-Id: If687ff005cf968133fc1fa12b1259a127c464e5b

Remove versionutils

The versionutils module has graduated, so remove the incubated version
and update remaining references to the version in oslo.log.

Blueprint graduate-oslo-versionutils

'}, {'created': '2015-03-30 03:28:28.000000000', 'message': 'Complete switch to snapshot objects

The following patch switches the remainder of cinder internals
to use snapshot object instead of direct db calls.  Note that
db calls within cinder drivers were not switched over.  This
is left to driver maintainers to do themselves and to
properly test out the changes on their hardware.

Also, note that there are three occurrences of
db.snapshot_update left in cinder/volume/manager.py.  This is
intentional because driver.create_cgsnapshot and
driver.delete_cgsnapshot returns a list of snapshot dicts.
cgsnapshots must be switched over to objects before these
occurrences can be safely removed and changed to use object
methods.

Change-Id: I64004ac404f67eecee51361dc8edd3f149e1b987
Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

The following patch switches the remainder of cinder internals
to use snapshot object instead of direct db calls.  Note that
db calls within cinder drivers were not switched over.  This
is left to driver maintainers to do themselves and to
properly test out the changes on their hardware.

Also, note that there are three occurrences of
db.snapshot_update and one of db.snapshot_destroy left in
cinder/volume/manager.py.  This is intentional because
driver.create_cgsnapshot and driver.delete_cgsnapshot returns
a list of snapshot dicts.  Each driver needs to switched over
occurences of db.snapshot_get_all_for_cgsnapshot() to
SnapshotList.get_all_for_cgsnapshot() in create_cgsnapshot
and delete_cgsnapshot.  Once each driver has done so, a follow
up patch can be created to remove db.snapshot_update and
db.snapshot_destroy in cinder/volume/manager.py.  There are
bugs filed for these to be fixed -
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bugs?field.tag=
cgsnapshot-objects.

Change-Id: I64004ac404f67eecee51361dc8edd3f149e1b987

commit_message:
Complete switch to snapshot objects

The following patch switches the remainder of cinder internals
to use snapshot object instead of direct db calls.  Note that
db calls within cinder drivers were not switched over.  This
is left to driver maintainers to do themselves and to
properly test out the changes on their hardware.

Also, note that there are three occurrences of
db.snapshot_update and one of db.snapshot_destroy left in
cinder/volume/manager.py.  This is intentional because
driver.create_cgsnapshot and driver.delete_cgsnapshot returns
a list of snapshot dicts.  Each driver needs to switched over
occurences of db.snapshot_get_all_for_cgsnapshot() to
SnapshotList.get_all_for_cgsnapshot() in create_cgsnapshot
and delete_cgsnapshot.  Once each driver has done so, a follow
up patch can be created to remove db.snapshot_update and
db.snapshot_destroy in cinder/volume/manager.py.  There are
bugs filed for these to be fixed -
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bugs?field.tag=
cgsnapshot-objects.

Change-Id: I64004ac404f67eecee51361dc8edd3f149e1b987
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

commit_message:
Clean up unused exceptions

Over the last cycle several drivers were removed. There
have also been changes over time in the code. As a
result, there were quite a few exception class declarations
that were no longer being used anywhere in the code base.

This removes Exception classes that were not referenced.

Change-Id: Ieed6e6e81196e7fe62d0ce22bab5620ac4a1269d

commit_message:
Allow provisioning to reach max oversubscription

Currently if provisioned ratio is equal to max_over_subscription_ratio,
the capacity filter does not allow any more thin provisioning. This patch
makes a change so that thin provisioning is allowed if provisioned ratio
is equal to max_over_subscription_ratio; it will only stop provisioning
if provisioned ratio is greater than max_over_subscription_ratio.

Change-Id: Ibf13ef97472b80a1b59ffd4389a4ed2eacf67205
Partial-Bug: #1458976
(cherry picked from commit ab017d98b1bb39d218bd93970c0e561c685b7dbf)

host_state, because if only few of backends supply filter_function
in a multibackend deployment, there will be lots of warning log
for those backends don't supply for EVERY create request.

UpgradeImpact:
DriverFilter had an undocumented side-effect before it evluates
filter_function - it checked if volume_backend_name in host_state
reported by backend matches volume_backend_name in volume type
extra specs, and if they don't, the backend would fail to pass
the filter.  Now that this side-effect has been removed, it
would impact users only under following circumstance: 1) user
enabled DriverFilter but not CapabilitiesFilter; 2) user relied
on DriverFilter to filter backends based on exact match of
'volume_backend_name' in type extra spec.  If unfortunately this
is the case for user, enabling CapabilitiesFilter by adding
it to 'scheduler_default_filters' configure option and restart
cinder scheduler service then everything should work just fine.
CapabilitiesFilter actually does a much better job checking
volume_backend_name.

commit_message:
DriverFilter: don't check volume_backend_name

Currently DriverFilter checks if host_state.volume_backend_name
matches type.extra_specs.volume_backend_name.  The same check has
already been done in CapabilitiesFilter and done more thoroughly and
gracefully, for example, volume_backend_name can be a set of names
not limited to one to one match.  DriverFilter should just do one
thing, that is evaluating filter_function supplied by backend.

This change removes the volume_backend_name check from DriverFilter
without touching its core function, thus has no impact on existing
documentation because the checking of volume_backend_name is an
undocumented side-effect of this filter.  This change also reduces
one warning log to debug log when no filter_function found in
host_state, for the reason it would generate a lot of warning log
for those backends don't supply filter_function.

UpgradeImpact:
DriverFilter had an undocumented side-effect before it evaluates
filter_function - it checked if volume_backend_name in host_state
reported by backend matches volume_backend_name in volume type
extra specs, and if they don't, the backend would fail to pass
the filter.  Now that this side-effect has been removed, it
would impact users only under following circumstance: 1) user
enabled DriverFilter but not CapabilitiesFilter; 2) user relied
on DriverFilter to filter backends based on exact match of
'volume_backend_name' in type extra spec.  If unfortunately this
is the case for user, enabling CapabilitiesFilter by adding
it to 'scheduler_default_filters' configure option and restart
cinder scheduler service then everything should work just fine.
CapabilitiesFilter actually does a much better job checking
volume_backend_name.

Change-Id: Ie5c48587368856faa538eebb1b6611d464bd69bd
Closes-bug: #1461770

- gate-project-config-jenkins-project http://logs.openstack.org/96/187196/4/check/gate-project-config-jenkins-project/dc1475d/ : SUCCESS in 21s'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-06-01 20:50:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Thanks for coming up with this idea!

I do not think we're ready to do this yet, but we may be in the future.  Here's what I think we should do first:

Both Rally and Nova (and possibly other projects) have expressed an interest in this kind of delegation. First, I think they should try the process manually so that it is easy to implement and change, and we are certain that we like the idea before we build automation and tooling around it.

Second, if after a while we decide that it is working well and we would like automation, I think we should look into implementing prolog rules for this.  I am not certain what options we have there (for instance, I don't know if we can provide custom feedback strings like "Needs Code-Review from plugin group") or if there are bugs that need fixing (there is a known bug with searching for review labels from a group).  However, I believe the general idea of adding rules like "if a changes touches these files, it needs a review from this group" should be supported.

https://review-dev.openstack.org/Documentation/prolog-cookbook.html
https://review-dev.openstack.org/Documentation/prolog-change-facts.html

A major reason to avoid adding a new category is because it is confusing to users.  It is not immediately clear what the difference between Code-Review and Plugin-Review is, and the ability for someone to leave a -1 and +1 in those categories is also potentially confusing.  It's not a show-stopper, but I believe that makes looking into prolog first a good idea.

If, after we decide that the process works, and prolog is not sufficient, and that adding a new column is the best idea, then we can proceed.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-06-01 21:22:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

James, 

Actually, this was just attempt to scale up review process by adding new group of cores that reviews only plugins. 
So it will be enough to have 1 +2 from such person and 1 +2 from core reviewer to merge patch. 

This will allow us to add at least for now 3 more "plugin" cores instantly  and increase drastically throughput.
 (we have almost open 150 code reviews and should do something with that asap).

P.S. Rally team would like to have at least this for now and it doesn't seem to be too complicated..

------

The full story. 

I was looking for solution to make cores of subdirectories. 
(Actually this is how Linux development process is organized)

There will be maintainers for various subdirectories e.g.: 
rally/plugins/* , rally/verification/* or rally/benchmark/* 

I started discussion (in gerrit community) :
https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/repo-discuss/2c0CJcR1w4s

And they send me to the gerrit Prolog. 

If Infra is ready to support custom Prolog rules for various projects I really would like to join this effort!'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-06-06 21:07:18.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Improve Rally ACL rules

Add extra column with core plugin reviews:

 - We can split core reviewers and plugin reviewers and increase review
   throughtput (by social rules like 1 plugin reviewer + 1 core
   reviewer is enough to merge plugin patch)

 - Plugin core reviewers should be able to block changes with -2
   if something is terribly wrong

 - Any mark in core plugin reviews, except -2, is non blocking

Add rally-release group for pushing tags

Change-Id: I671d5c21186c7e1c4667f2e434c01c46ac5ebab3

Or improvise :)'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-06-01 17:52:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks Sean, unfortunately that method only works correctly if you have a single commit that adds the driver. Due to us having a dependent change it needs more than just a single cherry-pick. When doing multiple cherry-pick the ordering of them breaks things and the cherry-picks won't apply cleanly. When the apply fails, cinder fails to start the driver, and the tests fail.

What we do now is detect if it is running the job for this review and decide if we need to cherry-pick the commits or not. The end result being that we pass on *all* reviews and not just reviews other than this one.... If you check the history for our CI it has been building successfully with the FC driver for several days on other cinder reviews."}, {'account_id': 5149, 'date': '2015-06-01 17:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add Pure Storage FibreChannel driver

    This commit adds a FibreChannel driver for Pure Storage. The driver shares
    the majority of functionality with base driver and only has the code
    necessary to support connection to FibreChannel.

Implements: blueprint pure-fc-driver
Change-Id: Ia4ce76d6a2ec754951c13d3620f9f47d6920058b

[{'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-01-30 18:20:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-01-30 18:21:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-30 19:02:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-swift-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/28/151728/1/check/gate-swift-specs-docs/aeba93c//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 39s'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-01-30 19:53:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

"SLO" already has a meaning in Swift: "Static Large Objects".

Speaking of static large objects, this whole thing can be accomplished client-side by creating different containers with different storage policies, uploading objects appropriately, and then using single-segment SLO manifests as pointers.

This is just as easy on application writers as the proposed spec; instead of making the application writer pass along some X-Service-Level-Objective header or whatever, the application writer has to PUT the object in a container with the right storage policy and then create a single-segment manifest in the "real" location. Both require client-side code changes, but the latter works with Swift today.'}, {'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-02-04 22:24:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Samuel Merrit: Thanks for your comment. Here is my response:

One way of depositing objects in the right backend as described by the “Hybrid container” proposal can be accomplished by having that decision made by the client and by leveraging Swift’s existing storage policies. That definitely serves the use case of applications that wish to include the appropriate segregation in their logic as well as tailored to the Storage Policies that were available at the Swift Cluster at the time of the application writing or configuration. It can be done today with existing Swift and it will remain an important feature that the new proposal does not wish to conflict with.
 
The new proposal is addressing a different use case where the operator of the Swift cluster would like add new devices transparent to the application that might better serve the needs of the data being stored as well the operational objectives of seeking the best TCO (total cost of ownership – here storage). This fact is especially true for cold/archival storage tier where retention can span multiple hardware generations and media types (archival drives, 3D flash, optical). There will one set of applications that will actively refactor their internal logic to adapt to the inclusion of multi-generational hardware and media. However, a (likely) bigger set will find it hard to be constantly modified to deal with changes in the underlying infrastructure. It is for these use cases that we propose to introduce an application-transparent operator-controlled means to depositing the objects to the right backend.
 
The inclusion of this use case as a basic feature will allow customers/operators seeking Swift as a long term data retention platform to non-disruptively update their infrastructure without the worry of breaking application stacks.'}, {'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-02-04 22:34:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry for the formatting of the my last post. I'm reposting my response 
(with max 80 character per line):

@Samuel Merritt: Thanks for your comment. Here is my response:

One way of depositing objects in the right backend as described by the “Hybrid
container” proposal can be accomplished by having that decision made by the
client and by leveraging Swift’s existing storage policies. That definitely
serves the use case of applications that wish to include the appropriate
segregation in their logic as well as tailored to the Storage Policies that were
available at the Swift Cluster at the time of the application writing or
configuration. It can be done today with existing Swift and it will remain an
important feature that the new proposal does not wish to conflict with.
 
The new proposal is addressing a different use case where the operator of the
Swift cluster would like add new devices transparent to the application that
might better serve the needs of the data being stored as well the operational
objectives of seeking the best TCO (total cost of ownership – here storage).
This fact is especially true for cold/archival storage tier where retention can
span multiple hardware generations and media types (archival drives, 3D flash,
optical). There will one set of applications that will actively refactor their
internal logic to adapt to the inclusion of multi-generational hardware and
media. However, a (likely) bigger set will find it hard to be constantly
modified to deal with changes in the underlying infrastructure. It is for these
use cases that we propose to introduce an application-transparent
operator-controlled means to depositing the objects to the right backend.
 
The inclusion of this use case as a basic feature will allow customers/operators
seeking Swift as a long term data retention platform to non-disruptively update
their infrastructure without the worry of breaking application stacks."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-02-20 23:34:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I guess I'll downgrade to -1 in case other folks really want it, but it seems like an impossible thing to do. 

If you ask me, a moderately-intelligent human being, to take my app's Swift objects and optimally place them for cost vs. performance, I can probably get most of them right (assuming enough coffee, no distractions, etc. etc.).

If you ask me to write code for my app to place Swift objects optimally, it won't do quite as well as a human, but it might still be okay.

If you ask me to guess how to place some random person's app's Swift objects, I'm not going to do very well at all. All I can do is guess based on file sizes and ages.

If you ask me to write code to guess how to place some random person's app's Swift objects, it's going to be like a comedy of errors, only not funny.

Even if the whole community comes together and consumes enough coffee to drown an elephant and focuses all their effort on the classifier and somehow, through positively superhuman feats of coding, gets the classifier up to 99.999% accuracy, that's still thousands of mistakes per day on a moderate-size Swift cluster, every one of which could result in a support ticket."}, {'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-02-27 19:56:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Samuel, I understand that your mental model is that Swift needs to “guess” optimal 
placement of objects for cost/performance, which may lead to suboptimal decisions.

Placement of objects in a Hybrid Container will be deterministic based on a
mapping between storage classes offered by the Swift operator and the type of
backend devices (or storage policies) supported within a cluster.  For example,
an “IOPS-optimized” class can be mapped to SSD devices and an “GB-optimized”
class to an HDD devices.  This allows Swift provider to publish various storage
classes where each class is associated with a cost and a set of well-defined
performance/reliability properties.

The concept of storage class is supported by Amazon S3. 

With the knowledge of the cost and the properties of each storage class,
an application can choose the right class to meet its needs.  An application may
specify the storage class on an ingest explicitly, e.g., by passing it through a
header on a PUT operation, akin to  S3  "x-amz-storage-class” header. Or, it may
specify the class implicitly through a set of rules based on object properties.
An example for such a rule is to associate IOPS-optimized class to objects
smaller than a certain threshold, and GB-optimized class to objects larger than
the threshold.  Based on this rule, Swift cluster infers the storage class
requirement of the object during ingest from the object size, and determines the
right storage class.

Since a Swift cluster has the knowledge of its backend devices (or storage
policies), it is the logical place to make the decision about where to place an
object to honor the storage class associated with the object.

In summary, a) the mapping between a storage class and backend devices (or
storage policies) are deterministic, b) applications explicitly or implicitly
specify the storage class per object, and c) placement of objects are best
enforced at the Swift level.

I hope my response clarifies the confusion around how object placement would work in
Hybrid Container.'}, {'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-03-27 20:02:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Waiting for further comments.'}, {'account_id': 14735, 'date': '2015-03-31 19:43:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Some details of our design is available at:
http://www.slideshare.net/SaeedGhanbari/hybridcontainer

We plan to share the code shortly. We will discuss the implementation details with the community during the Vancouver summit.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-02 09:31:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

(16 comments)

I did not find this document helpful.

Some of the general characteristics described made sense intuitively - but it feels disconnected from where the project is here and now.

A big part of this document seems to be advocating for different storage backends - storage policies - which we already have an implementation that's working well and evolving.

Then the next part seems to be advocating for object markers - which is single file static object manifests - which we already have an implementation for that's working well and evolving [1].

I think you need to do some work understanding what's available in Swift today.  If you think you see a deficiency you might try getting on IRC or the ML and asking how deployers and developers are solving those challenges today - maybe you could do the same - or maybe after you try them out - you'll find better ways to do it, or see ways they could be improved.

Last thing, you just *can't* use the acronym SLO so close to Swift and it not mean Static Large Object - it's the same problem with marketing people acting like a PR is a press release.  Nope, it's a pull request.  Please fix that if you choose to resubmit.

1. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155421/"}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-06-06 19:21:20.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Abandoning based on the negative reviews (including the -2) and the lack of activity since then. If you'd like to further develop this idea, you can re-open this patch or submit something new.

However, know that there have been some recent conversation at the last summit to support similar features but to work more with the building blocks that Swift already has. If you have any questions, please feel free to get in IRC and ask."}]

commit_message:
Remove entity headers on 304 response

As per RFC 2616 section 10.3.5 & section 4.3, 304 Not Modified
should not include entity headers like Content-Length & Content-Type.

Change-Id: I51006fe15e82acc1e3f23227f767bd802998f189

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- gate-swift-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/29/108229/1/check/gate-swift-specs-docs/ea47595 : FAILURE in 52s'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-07-22 20:53:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't speak for every Swift core developer, but personally, I have zero interest in this feature.

Swift is an object storage system, not an API translation layer. Swift provides durable, available, and eventually-consistent storage from a set of failure-prone, flaky, and immediately-consistent disks.

Also, it appears that the proposed translation layer would require the use of Keystone. Swift supports a variety of pluggable authentication mechanisms, and features are not tied to particular auth systems.

Further, if this spec were to lead to code, I wouldn't want to test it since it'll cost me money. It's one thing to ask reviewers to spend time reviewing and testing changes; that's just something we do. However, if I have to take out *my* credit card to test *your* change, I'm not going to test it.

If you want to build an API translation layer for Swift -> S3 so that Swift-API clients can use S3 (or whatever other object store you have laying around), then there's nothing wrong with that. However, it does not belong in Swift.

This is all just my opinion, of course, and other core devs can feel free to overrule me should they so choose."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-07-28 17:50:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

I completely agree with Sam's assessment."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-06-06 19:09:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This is not something that fits with the current project goals.'}]

commit_message:
Move Dothill tests out of root test directory

The Dothill code merged but unfortunately had it's
unit tests in the base tests directory.

This patch just moves it to tests/unit/volume/drivers

Change-Id: I010ed2f784384e272599ec3139957989f8838e6f
Closes-Bug: #1462106

Mark all current deprecations to get removed before 1.0

The active/current deprecations should not exist when version
1.0 is released so noting that in the code will let users become
aware of this so that they may prepare for it.

commit_message:
Add a test that checks for task result visibility

Now that a task can provide the same thing that it
requires, having a nice little test that ensures what
is gotten is expected in a nice manner should be done
to make sure what a task will be getting for its arguments
respect the scoping that is defined by the flow ordering.

Change-Id: I1cdc5c3bd3f56b39f20f28f51c36017405150cea

commit_message:
Fix remaining memory issues with nfs backup unit tests

Here we fix another place in the nfs backup unit tests where
the configured file size was larger than the chunk size in
the corresponding Swift backup tests.  I missed this one in

   https://review.openstack.org/#/c/165394

and even though code with that fix ran fine in a bare 1GB VM,
there are still memory issues when run in CI with a VM of that
size.

Closes-Bug: 1452811

commit_message:
StorPool: use the ABC metaclasses for volume drivers

Declare the existing StorPool volume driver functionality by
deriving from the appropriate driver.*VD classes.

Implements: blueprint abc-driver-update
Change-Id: I752b2420a3b4459e4311d2e7b5e8a0a748fb1b73

commit_message:
StorPool: implement volume retyping and migrations

initialize_connection(): store the StorPool client ID in the connection
data to be used by the "StorPool" Brick connector.

validate_connector(): actually check the connector data for a valid
hostname defined in the StorPool configuration.

_storpool_client_id(): new method to get the numeric ID of a host in
the StorPool cluster from the /etc/storpool.conf file.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): if the "remote" flag is set, pass
the request on to the default Cinder driver implementation; it knows
how to make remote volumes accessible.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): support the case when these methods
are invoked from a method that is not overridden in the StorPool Cinder
driver - create a storpool.spopenstack.AttachDB attachment structure
and destroy it upon detaching.

ensure_export(): add a stub method, the actual work is handled by
the Nova volume attachment driver.

retype(): new method: handle a StorPool-to-StorPool retyping where
at most the volume's StorPool template or replication is changed.
For anything else, return False to indicate an unsupported request so
that a full volume migration is triggered.

update_migrated_volume(): rename the StorPool volume to correspond to
the real Cinder volume's name.

Add the StorPoolConfigurationMissing and StorPoolConfigurationInvalid
exceptions.

Flesh out the validate_connector() and initialize_connection() unit tests.

Implements: blueprint volume-retype
Change-Id: I82925c2bf45dff839706f518d4d790b8596ff492

commit_message:
StorPool: fall back to the configured template

If the volume type does not specify a template, properly fall back to
the default template from the configuration instead of going with none.

Change-Id: I7622eba3aa7ef95563e83c82363b690bfb42a2c0

Removed explicit return from __init__ method

As per python documentation [1], removed explicit return keyword
from __init__ method.

[1] https://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#object.__init__

Closes-Bug: 1461931

commit_message:
[rally-jobs] Change import of base context

Rally team wants to change structure of context module[*] and doesn't want to
break ec2 gates, so this patch adds try...except block to cover old structure
and new one.

try...except block should be removed, after patch in Rally will be merged.

[*] - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188518/

Also, this patch fixes wrong import of rally network wrapper

Depends-On: I29c2dd5f85dc8b0a59d9b3f0ea86ff3edf0a7953
Change-Id: I4a012c994dbbc6320f6d3c6b1537b47c6f1579e5

commit_message:
devstack/settings: Do not configure passwords here

Because openrc doesn't honour them.
They are user settings more suitable to local.conf anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1462166
Change-Id: Ifeb5a0be905688f401d223fc9c67d17999a7d5af

commit_message:
ngReorg - move dashboard controllers from horizon

This change moves the controller ImageFormCtrl and
hzNamespaceResourceTypeFormController from horizon (the framework)
to openstack_dashboard (the application) where they belong.

Co-Authored-By: Tyr Johanson <tyr@hp.com>
Change-Id: I2309f0867c2f657a6065003475dcb10448f907bc
Partial-Bug: #1458697
