commit_message:
Change new input task format specification

We have issue with current format there are 2 things called "task",
"task" is file with bunch of "task" that are run.

I would prefer to split these 2 things:

  task - is file that is run by "rally task" command

  subtasks - is actually single test case described in task file

Change-Id: Ib1a2f39bb91cfb5b0ba0b3d15be53d3a3241bfc7

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
tempest: add `admin_domain_name' to generated conf

Add admin_domain_name=default of autogenerated tempest.conf
This line prevents the keystone v3 related tests to be declared as failure.

Closes-Bug:1460680

Change-Id: I9e0eeb2e9392df17fc0e0c71bf9268482e921ac9
Signed-off-by: morganrOL <morgan.richomme@orange.com>

commit_message:
Add the Designate DNSaaS services.

This is a complete DNS solution, with hidden master and bind9 slave.

It lacks the designate-sink service, because there is no true specification
to implement that. It listens for Nova/Neutron events and creates records
though adding those to just 1 domain isn't helping much in an environment
with multiple tenants.

Change-Id: I500fb6058b118d25a4ccfd1d3479830c36af7e2a
Blueprint: designate-container

Change-Id: I2c92a7596a8faee28de582493bdf72425deac8cc
'}]
commit_message:
Added `npm run lint` command to execute JSCS

This patch adds jscs as an npm dependency, and executes it within
the npm venv. It can be used to trigger the infra npm-run-lint job
and thus get voting javascript code linting into infra.

Change-Id: I2c92a7596a8faee28de582493bdf72425deac8cc

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Add support to get a SwiftService object

This adds a property of the cloud, swift_service, for the purpose of
enabling uploads via SwiftService's more advanced segmenting
capabilities.

In writing tests, it became clear that cloud.swift_client was leaking
exceptions, which we don't want it to do, which is why we add exception
handling to that method.

Change-Id: I045266e6d5f0b6bed3100905ada6ab35fbb06987

commit_message:
Add delete method for security groups

Adds the API method to delete a security group, using nova or neutron,
and consolidates existing and new security group tests into a new file.

Change-Id: Ib85b3ec0de8b2b42f691c3e2127adb16e8b14c99

Now I am wondering if we could simply set the __native_bulk_support to False in Ml2Plugin and be done. Am I thinking straight here? If we set the native bulk support to False, the plugin will emulate the bulk operations (_emulate_bulk_create in neutron/api/v2/base.py) which essentially means calling the create on each item in the collection one by one. This will be ok as for non bulk operations only pre commit will be in the transaction for the create operation and post commit will be executed outside the transaction. If any of the create operations fails, the emulate bulk method, deltas those items already created (essentially does the roll back). Doing this breaks a bunch of unit tests but that is a different issue. 

Too late around here; will look into this more tomorrow.'}, {'account_id': 1923, 'date': '2014-09-19 06:09:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-13 19:24:03.000000000', 'message': 'Move postcommit ops out of transaction for bulk

Currently, the bulk create operations in ML2 are executed in
a transaction. This means all precommit and postcommit operations
for such operations are in a transaction. Postcommit operations
are expected to be executed outside of transactions as they may
communicate with a backend and introduce substantial delays. This
fix removes the postcommit operations from the transaction for
bulk create network operation. Bulk create ops for subnets and
ports are to be fixed using the same approach in a future patch set
or as seperate patches.

Change-Id: I9a9683058088e50d9443040223232bf5e1396ccf
Partial-Bug: #1193861

commit_message:
Move postcommit ops out of transaction for bulk

Currently, the bulk create operations in ML2 are executed in
a transaction. This means all precommit and postcommit operations
for such operations are in a transaction. Postcommit operations
are expected to be executed outside of transactions as they may
communicate with a backend and introduce substantial delays. This
fix removes the postcommit operations from the transaction for
bulk create network/subnet/port operations.

Change-Id: I9a9683058088e50d9443040223232bf5e1396ccf
Closes-Bug: #1193861

commit_message:
Check the result of compose cmd

A error occurred when use kolla script execution compose cmd,we
need check result of compose cmd.

This commit add check_compose to pre_start and check result of
compose cmd.

Change-Id: I959391aba440935cc66f4821c65700df89310849
Closes-Bug: #1447959

commit_message:
versionutils: switch from incubator version to oslo.log

Note that we require oslo.log >= 1.2.0 since it's the first release that
included the module.

Change-Id: I2b7d587d8c4b0c885873c9c8083abb8fc35780c9

commit_message:
Fix req.environ[SCRIPT_NAME] value.

The computation done inside 
/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/routes/middleware.py 
was leaving req.environ[SCRIPT_NAME] with a wrong value with 
a repeated text block. No code in keystone seems to use the 
value of this variable, hence it has escaped detection until
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177427/ which logs req URLs 
by using SCRIPT_NAME in the url construction (via
wsgiref.util.request_uri()).

I backtraced the execution flow to the middleware.py file 
from the keystone middleware components. Prepending a '/' 
to the mapper path used in the ExtensionsRouter seems harmless 
as well as seems to fix the problem. 

See log files before and after, from sample Jenkins runs.

BEFORE: http://goo.gl/YI89e4
AFTER (for this review): http://goo.gl/I1qVaI

Closes-Bug:#1454968

Change-Id: Ia9bf1e1644c996e5aa71ac4e634ead3c4de7edcf

commit_message:
Added karma-cli to package.json

Turns out that npm runs a little like venv's do, in that it can
install executables in its own path. This adds the karma-cli
executable into the npm path, and removes additional extraneous
content from the package.json file.

Change-Id: Ib25553956a9757ecbb1ee7ce722f3646ededc035

[{'created': '2014-08-20 07:02:32.000000000', 'message': "Fix swift-recon --auditor bug

I introduced a bug in swift-recon --auditor, which Christian
Schwede uncovered.  Christian proposed a fix which replaces the
generator nested_get_value with a recursive function which
returns just one instance of a key.  Christian's fix will break
the parallel object auditor patch which uses the generator to
return all instances of a particular key in a nested dictionary
and then sums those values.

This alternative fix sums over all values returned by
nested_get_value, as is done in the parallel auditor patch.

Change-Id: I6ac403395ab42d11161d6df266e8fbd5a2af9a64
(cherry picked from commit 203515718a2bee8334bd4936201f00a929ccbd89)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix swift-recon --auditor bug

I introduced a bug in swift-recon --auditor, which Christian
Schwede uncovered.  Christian proposed a fix which replaces the
generator nested_get_value with a recursive function which
returns just one instance of a key.  Christian's fix will break
the parallel object auditor patch which uses the generator to
return all instances of a particular key in a nested dictionary
and then sums those values.

This alternative fix sums over all values returned by
nested_get_value, as is done in the parallel auditor patch.

Change-Id: I6ac403395ab42d11161d6df266e8fbd5a2af9a64
(cherry picked from commit 203515718a2bee8334bd4936201f00a929ccbd89)

commit_message:
Make plugins location configurable

The patch introduces CLI option --plugin-paths to specify the list of
folders with plugins.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Vasilets <rvasilets@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ilya Shakhat <ishakhat@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Iee39217bfe3e5c77e6925910f3998942541387a3

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also

    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

LGTM.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-02-20 20:55:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

awwww man, what happened to this plan:

    It seems like it might be safest to just to have the auditor throw out
    tombstones older than reclaim age and leave the hashes.pkl and
    replication out of it

Won't this cause a bunch of rehashes and listdirs - not just on the node that first discovers the old tombstone but all the replicas of the part as well?

Why *can't* we just remove the tombstone and the hashdir and such?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-02-20 22:21:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Because then the hash is a lie. If you delete a tombstone and then don't update/invalidate the hash, you wind up where you can go and listdir() all the datadirs and MD5 everything, and the value you get doesn't match what's in hashes.pkl."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-02-20 22:57:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Well... I had reaped almost 50% dead inodes thanks to these. I did not see any ill effects from this code, but my cluster is really tiny. If there are questions about extra activity generated by this, maybe someone could be bold enough to run this patch. It could be installed on 1 node, it's compatible enough, I think."}, {'account_id': 14966, 'date': '2015-02-23 12:27:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-02-23 23:38:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@sam - so what?  the reason you invalidate hashes is to mark activity in the suffix to trigger replication.  Our problem isn't that we want in-active suffixes to be re-synced - we just want to free up the inodes.  We don't need to trigger replication on inactive suffixes - we just need to unlink the tombstones.

Deleting the tombstones w/o touching the suffix hashes seems like we get to have our cake and eat it too!  What's the harm of waiting for some real activity in the suffix before we make all replicas of a part do the rehash?"}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-02-24 01:48:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

FYI, I took this over because it was possible for my small mind to reason that this fix isn't going to break anything, unlike deleting tombstones willy-nilly. I do realize that additional load may be possible -- but it should not be present if things function as they should. I think maybe I provoked extra tombstones by restarting nodes and services for testing."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-02-26 21:22:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

clay: I guess that's true. It's just one more edge case to try to remember when I'm working on this stuff is all."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-02-26 21:23:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

So, this seems good. Invalidate the hash or not; either one works for me.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-02-26 22:39:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

I don't think this should be in diskfile

We open a diskfile on PUT - so if you're overwriting a really old tombstone we're calling invalidate twice.

The auditor already has a nice except change where DiskFileDeleted could inspect the e.timestamp and decide if the tombstone should be reaped.

Also I think we're calling invalidate suffix for ever old tombstone instead of just once for the suffix where old tombstones were discovered - seems like one more reason to just delete the tombstone and leave the hashes update and replication out of it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-14 18:05:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-16 05:25:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I wonder if we could use the Diskfile purge method to address this?'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-06-05 23:26:11.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning due to lack of activity since the last negative review. You can restore the change if you want to keep working on it.'}]

commit_message:
remove old tombstone(.ts)

Check tombstone in object-auditor, call invalidate_hash if found.

Since auditor now uses the reclaim_age as well as the replicator,
relocate the configuration variable into the [DEFAULT] section.

Closes-Bug: 1301728
Change-Id: I58c7377730cba2e885453ec24637f33318b6f7de
Modified-By: Pete Zaitcev <zaitcev@redhat.com>

About half of the test is on mocking the API, I think it might make sense to have a mocked version of each API. Travis also mentioned maybe using httpBackend, I need to do some reading on it but I think it might make sense to go in this direction. This way, it become re-usable in other tests. 

-1 is to ensure that we get this process underway, not intended to block if other cores feel the need to push through.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-04 23:39:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30: Code-Review-1

I think we could at least have some discussion on the mocking before merging... 

Here's some more on the mocking.  Please let me know if I'm missing something here.

This injects a bunch of value constants. Each of these value constants redefine the test functions from the actual APIs. What I see is that if we go off and change the APIs that nothing would get reflected here.  I could go and change an API signature and update API tests and happily go along thinking I didn't break anything, when in fact these value constants would be masking that changing the API actually broke all this code.  In addition, if we want to change APIs, we're going to have to go and search for everywhere that we recreate the APIs in value injections and then recreate them. That doesn't seem DRY.

Injecting the actual services and a $httpBackend would prevent us from hitting the above situation.

Maybe we could could instead create a mock for every api that sits next to it? e.g. hz.api.nova.mock.js. Those mocks would just extend the actual API, but inject $httpBackend taking away some boilerplate? These tests would then inject those mocks. Maybe the mock should take the expected data from these tests to promote visibility of the test data.  Just a little brainstorming.  Wanted to try it out, but ran out of time today."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-04 23:40:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30: Verified+1

Another possibility, these still could be pulled into some common test files hz.api.blah.mock.js even if they stay as values. And then they could perhaps at least have a test for them that ensures that they don't define functions that are in the real APIs (not a fan).

At least then they could be reused (which I think Matt also has some opinion on)."}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-05 13:17:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30:

Re Travis: "What I see is that if we go off and change the APIs that nothing would get reflected here."

This is *exactly* why we should continue doing what is being demonstrated here.  Unit tests should test code using a specific set of inputs and expected outputs (or behaviors involving other code).  If the runtime inputs (data in apis) are changing and it affects the code, the tests and mocks should change as well (or event respect multiple versions of data).  A modification of both inputs and expectations is required *any* time the code changes...otherwise the code wasn't being tested properly!

Please note, passthrough data that is not relevantly modified or used by code can and should be ignored--because this is a unit test and information extraneous to the code under test is irrelevant to the test.

So to be clear, we should certainly *not* be providing any kind of backend for API calls, etc.  That would be introducing functionality that is not relevant to the code under test.  I am all for having some sort of centralized provider of test API data.  But it would look almost exactly like what is contained in this file.  Furthermore, any centralized test code can only go so far, because each test writer will need to write many variations on the test code to ensure that all cases are handled, so you may end up with lots of additional mocking objects...which is completely normal and expected when writing good unit tests!

I understand that it seems like a lot of work and duplication.  But that's exactly what you need in unit tests...you are creating independent structures to test assumptions and expectations of the code.  You cannot base these assumptions on 'real' data but data in a vacuum, such as demonstrated here.

So going forward, I would be for possibly having a centralized set of test data, but understand even if we do that we will be creating many further structures local to the test necessary to test all the branches/conditionals.  So I don't think we gain a lot.

Yes, there seems to be "duplication" of data, but that's exactly how you write unit tests!  Static inputs and static expectations...doesn't matter if it's a single string or a complex data structure.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-05 15:30:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

So the Unit testing aspect and your concerns on separation I get, but what I don't think is being understood is that I'm concerned that the injected API can be changed completely (renamed, deleted, etc) and these value mocks will completely miss that and will completely mask that has happened. They are totally redefining the object interface. With non DI based testing, of course testing inputs and outputs is exactly what you want to do.  But when doing DI and completely re-writing the API locally (as with these value objects) then what is being injected has no actual relationship to the real API.  IMO, there is a definite fragility to that approach.

Would using something like Jasmine and.callFake work for this instead and remove some of this fragility? You can still inject the service and the use and.callFake to provide your own fake function.

See this jsfiddle:

If I add the following line:

        spyOn(foo, 'noexist').andCallFake(function () {
            return true;
        });

It will result in

noexist() method does not exist

You can try other combinations of this to see that it makes the mocking a little less problematic from the perspective I shared above.  I also think that a central mock sitting next to each API could reduce all that other boilerplate promise code in each of these value objects (defferred), but at least this much would be a step in that direction.  I also believe that my statement above was missed that the central mock for each API could just still take the expected data from the actual test."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-05 15:30:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30:

Missed the jsfiddle: http://jsfiddle.net/eitanp461/LTeFd/'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-05 16:21:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

It seems the whole point of DI is that you don't know what is going to be injected in, and it is precisely this decoupling that is essential to modularizing your code.

What you want is in fact more of a runtime/integration test.  Something that makes sure that, when it's all put together, works.  That is expressly *not* what a unit test does.  Let's build some good integration tests for that purpose...but not in our unit tests.  :)"}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-05 16:35:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30:

With regard to reusing data for input and expectation, this is a bit of a philosophical issue that I discussed with Tyr yesterday.

Basically, if you have a test like:
a = "foo"
b = "bar"
expect(appenderFunc(a, b)).toBe(a + b)

That is kind of bad, because you're basically functionally replicating the method under test, as part of your test.  So you should really say:

expect(appendFunc(a, b)).toBe("foobar")

...even though it seems duplicative.

Same for a doublerFunc:

a = 2
expect(doublerFunc(a)).toBe(a*2)

is problematic.  Now extend that logic out a bit.

a = { some {complex: object}}
expect(transmogrifier(a)).toBe({thing: a})

It seems really nice to have it short and sweet, but it's really doing the same thing as above...it's essentially replicating some of the functionality of the test to generate the expectation.  That defies the idea of a test that is static on inputs and on expectations, if the expectation floats with the input.

Basically, what you find is that your expectation should be static.  So you should say:

a = { some {complex: object}}
expect(transmogrifier(a)).toBe({thing: { some {complex: object}}})

I know, what a pain!  But it's completely clear what the result should be, and avoids problems where, for example, 'a' gets mangled in the processing of transmogrifier() (which is a real concern).

Does that help clarify why you shouldn't reuse objects on inputs and expects?'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-05 16:36:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30:

Second, I'm not sure whether or not this is a good idea. Right now, Swift pretty much guarantees you read-after-write consistency for new objects: after you PUT an object, you can GET it again. I'm not sure if this would impact that or not."}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-01-23 08:17:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Hi Samuel,

Thank you.
I will surely add unit test for this change.
I agree with your comment. But my change here is for the case when an account is deleted, GET operation on object is successful. In my opinion it is not the right behavior.

How can an object be accessed if the account doesn't exists?
Please let me know your opinion on it."}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-02-05 09:28:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-02-05 09:31:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-02-05 09:37:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 10:12:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

(My draft just changed some wording in the commit message -- nits -- feel free to revert if you don't like)

I'm neutral/undecided on this change. From an account life-cycle point of view, I think it's better that when an account is deleted, that GET object should return 404 as soon as the account is deleted, rather than waiting until the account-reaper gets around to the object. As-is, I guess after an account is deleted you get a semi-random behavior (some objects are ok, others are gone).

From a resiliency point of view, it's nice that the account servers hosting the db files can be down, yet you can still get an object. With storage policies, I guess we now need the container db files to be up so we use the appropriate ring.

I'm leaning towards approval: if the system has enough failures that you can't get account info, you are probably getting 404s for objects anyway."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 12:30:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

looks good to me'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-03-02 08:13:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

@Madhuri, thanks for this patch. My understanding is swift works based on the CAP theorem (specially eventually consistent) so we need to handle the following patterns with eventually consistent behaviors like reaper, updater and replicator. 

http://paste.openstack.org/show/184755/

i.e. In pattern no.3, when an object puts, updates to a container fails. In this case updater will update the container info later.
i.e. In pattern no.5, deletes container while an object is uploading. In this case the container will be re-created later.

I think this logic works under consistent situation but we need to think more about in-consistent situation for the patterns. What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-03-20 05:57:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Hisashi, Thank you for the explanation. But I have few questions here:

1. In pattern no.5, how the container will be recreated and by whom?

2. From pattern no.2 to 31, what could be the expected status?

3. Just for example, what would the case when an account doesn't exists and the container and objects belonging to the same account exists i.e. pattern no.17?

And I am not sure how this pattern has been drawn. I would appreciate if you can explain.

Thanks in advance :)"}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-03-23 09:26:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Madhuri, Sorry to respond you late. I answer your questions below:

1. The object-server and/or the object-updater notify objects in the container then the container-server behaves like the container still exists (actually is not re-created).

2. I don't have it. I think this is the difficult point of this patch. To realize this patch we need to deal with the patterns whether it related or not.

3. As regards No.17, this case could be when account deletion and object put work in parallel. I drew the matrix with combination of the resources (account, container and object) and their relationship (the container in list ...). I think nearly every behaviors are covered with the patterns but most patterns might be difficult to produce."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-14 18:05:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Let GET/HEAD on object fail in deleted account.

Until now the GET/HEAD was successful on object of
deleted account. Now this patch will check for
the existence of container (which also checks
the existence of account) on object GET/HEAD and
return 404 if it doesn't exist.

Change-Id: I4f4192ef0c2fad5839308ce22027915a62576715
Closes-Bug: 1381541

This patch implements these parts of the blueprint:
1) Implements support for the keystone_service resource using
the v3 api.  With v3, service create requires the _type_, not
the _name_, so create has been changed accordingly.  Also note
that service list with the v3 api does not take the --long

the v2 service list --long.  The service id is used with destroy
and set rather than the name.  All of these implementation details
are hidden from manifests, which should continue to work the same
as before.

commit_message:
support for keystone v3 api - the service resource

Implements: blueprint api-v3-support
This patch implements these parts of the blueprint:
1) Implements support for the keystone_service resource using
the v3 api.  With v3, service create requires the _type_, not
the _name_, so create has been changed accordingly.  Also note
that service list with the v3 api does not take the --long
argument, but all of the same information is there as it is with
the v2 service list --long.  The service id is used with destroy
and set rather than the name.  All of these implementation details
are hidden from manifests, which should continue to work the same
as before.

Change-Id: Ia06dfb75f6e166d04ad151c87064ece85c7a8271
Co-Authored-By: Rich Megginson <rmeggins@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Decompose db_base_plugin_v2.py part 2

This patch contains method moving with minor modifications like updating
class names. IPAM specific methods were moved into ipam_backend_mixin and
ipam_non_pluggable_backend.

ipam_backend_mixin - contains code common for both backends (pluggable and
non-pluggable).

ipam_non_pluggable_backend - contains code specific for non-pluggable
IPAM implementation.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I6d68e4066ca472107def197c5a5afccbb6886a0e

commit_message:
Catch OSError in replicator if directory is gone.

If we have multiple replicator processes, (which can happen
if someone decides they need to start more manually to be
more aggressive with cleaning up deleted handoffs), the running
replicator can come across a partition directory that may alread
have been cleaned up by another.  This just catches that and
prevents the logs from getting exceptions.

This also adds some more unit testing around update_deleted
which didn't explicitly exist before, though was likely
most captured in other tests.

Change-Id: Idfd18f53173dbe649c58213044c142b883bc5bbe
Closes-Bug: #1397668

However there're some internal COPY requests are not using this,

This patch adds a check when DELETE/PUT on versioning manifest and

'}]
commit_message:
Fixes versioning SLO objects

Copying SLO manifest file already works if multipart-manifest=get
was specified by the client.

However some internal COPY requests are not following this,
the manifest header was not copied: 1) DELETE an old version
2) PUT a new version on a versioning SLO manifest file.

This patch adds a check when DELETE/PUT on versioning manifest and
make sure multipart-manifest=get used in COPY requests.

Closes-Bug: 1365862
Change-Id: Ie039a03d37b77f3f97cdb7a58f2432608efba091

commit_message:
Update paths to hooks in manila tempest job

Currently used hooks from "multi_backend" dir are redundant mediators.
So, replace usage of mediators with target scripts. It also will
allow to delete these redundant mediators in Manila project.

Change-Id: I1540d269430bd158afb9c009e48bfd33e2c4108f

commit_message:
Adding augeas insertion check.
Augeas change call will fail if key does not exists in policy.json.
This fix will add the key/value if it doesn't exists or will change the
value to match.
Added unit test.
Change-Id: Ibd97228c431fa6b23e8a15ce548f82f649131cc2

commit_message:
VolMgr: reschedule only when filter_properties has retry

In the task flow for volume manager, create_volume tasks, volume gets
reschedule even when scheduler doesn't indicate so.  The problem is
the flow should not only check 'allow_reschedule' and 'request_specs',
but also (more importantly) filter_properties['retry'], which is
populated by scheduler if schedule_max_attempts is set to > 1.  This
checks was there before taskflow was introduced, but somehow the
migration missed the check for filter_properties['retry'].

This change adds back the check, so scheduler_max_attempts won't be
treated like scheduler_max_attempts = infinite.

Change-Id: Ia873617b22a2d86662ea8ea2fec5aae7f54a2058
Closes-bug: #1445561
(cherry picked from commit 217f4dfb13714f583deeaeded66d36fb558e4b02)

commit_message:
Cloning cue-dashboard

This is needed because devstack integration with cue clones
the cue-dashboard project. However, this will fail because
cloning is not allowed in devstack-gate configuration. So
I am cloning this project prior to that.

Change-Id: Ice1412a999f682b022e28e063ec092c5d46fcfc6

commit_message:
Add tacker-horizon repo for Tacker project

Tacker is an OpenStack based ETSI MANO VNF Manager service.
This repository maintains the required Horizon UI enhancements
for Tacker

commit_message:
Fix concat file mode

The concat module passes the file permissions straight through to a file
resource, so for this to work in future parser then the mode has to be a
quoted string.

Change-Id: Iddfa6416e68127f874ce38edcdf1e208def2473f

commit_message:
Handle both string and array for memcache param.

Evaluation Error: Left match operand must result in a String value. Got
an Array. at .../modules/swift/manifests/proxy/cache.pp:26:6

Please note that Puppet syntax, while it defines a regex type, does NOT
permit regex type arguments to be passed to functions (as literals or
assigned to variables).

Change-Id: Ia230720e2cafb5b03404cea1ba54dd3b0ced6af3
Closes-Bug: #1449272
Signed-off-by: Robin H. Johnson <robbat2@gentoo.org>

commit_message:
read_affinity requires affinity sorting_method

proxy-server.conf read_affinity setting has no
effect unless sorting_method is set to 'affinity'

Change-Id: Ife0a30158289ea1dd44c1e93f058538c45c3a9c8

commit_message:
Fix ipv6 support

One shold never parse uri with split(':') as it was in types
ring_account_device, ring_container_device and ring_object_device.
This is fixed by using uri and just setting variables from that.
Also swift_ring_builder didn't add brackets to ipv6 address before
adding port information to it.

Change-Id: I55b7032143c8446abeed4f6c266c0fff0cb6b3b3

commit_message:
Add support for identity_uri.

This patch adds the ability to set a new identity_uri parameter.
It also deprecates the old auth_host, auth_port, auth_protocol,
and auth_admin_prefix parameters. Logic is in place so that
users of the deprecated settings should have a smooth upgrade
process and get deprecation warnings until they adopt the
new settings.

Change-Id: Ideefb4d824cbd5b4b83f9eb773a75e536e3458fb

commit_message:
Add base `swift` class name to call

When the ring server manifest `swift::ringserver` is called
the client throws and error with missing class. The module
`swift::ringserver` appears to refer to an incorrect class of
`Class['ringbuilder']` which should be `Class['swift::ringbuilder']`.

Change-Id: I9ddb12d2614440fe245aaaa10b7b17781a742f37
Implements: Add swift base class name to class call
Closes-Bug: 1414900

[{'created': '2015-01-27 03:16:39.000000000', 'message': "Swift proxy won't start if using proxy:ceilometer

The Swift ceilometer middleware needs to be able to
write its log file in the /var/log/ceilometer
directory. Not all distributions set permissions
on this directory such that the swift user/group
can write into the ceilometer log directory. This
can cause the swift-proxy to fail to startup due
to permissions issues.

This patch updates the swift::proxy::ceilometer so
that we create an empty /var/log/ceilometer/swift-proxy-server.log
file with proper permissions before starting the swift-proxy
service.

Change-Id: If7b88bf51046317171f6fa85bb8c01390fa26a37
"}]
commit_message:
Swift proxy won't start if using proxy:ceilometer

The Swift ceilometer middleware needs to be able to
write its log file in the /var/log/ceilometer
directory. Not all distributions set permissions
on this directory such that the swift user/group
can write into the ceilometer log directory. This
can cause the swift-proxy to fail to startup due
to permissions issues.

This patch updates the swift::proxy::ceilometer so
that we create an empty /var/log/ceilometer/swift-proxy-server.log
file with proper permissions before starting the swift-proxy
service.

Change-Id: If7b88bf51046317171f6fa85bb8c01390fa26a37

commit_message:
Add seed parameter to ringbuilder::rebalance.

This patch adds an optional seed parameter to the
swift::ringbuilder::rebalance definition. The seed
parameter can be useful if you want to (manually)
generate rings on independant servers and ensure that
the partition assignments are the same.

Change-Id: I840b8fe0125ed25e84f7681fada1b1102e48f32b

[{'created': '2014-09-05 22:44:22.000000000', 'message': "Allow setting reseller_prefix for keystone filter

When using keystone, it's possible to modify the behaviour to
use a different prefix instead of the default AUTH_.

This patch allows you to be able to set that option when
declaring your class definition.

Change-Id: I11ff23d118e0f3d1792b43e1dc7a2c82c6826427
"}]
commit_message:
Allow setting reseller_prefix for keystone filter

When using keystone, it's possible to modify the behaviour to
use a different prefix instead of the default AUTH_.

This patch allows you to be able to set that option when
declaring your class definition.

Change-Id: I11ff23d118e0f3d1792b43e1dc7a2c82c6826427

commit_message:
Add automaton adoption project changes

This was recently approved to be an oslo subproject:

- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141961/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184837/

Other items at:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.utils/+spec/adopt-automaton

This adds hopefully all of the needed config adjustments
to make this import correctly so that it can be worked
on and improved (from its initial repo where it was
extracted from).

Change-Id: Ieea0a39f9bdf78227a16f106b860891bfac2e83e

commit_message:
Allow create_object to create objects

create_object is a little different than other calls in that it sends
raw bytes in the body, so the create call inside the Resource is a bit
different. We hadn't hooked it up properly from the proxy either.

Change-Id: I01addbb70d57b7d9c24b3cc103153f06af6f10d7

Since Neutron is implementing it's own verison of the "Big Tent"

commit_message:
Add #openstack-neutron-release channel

Since Neutron is implementing it's own verison of the "Big Tent"
governance model (called the "Neutron Stadium"), I'd like to create
a new IRC channel we can use to sync release activities and to use
as a sync point between the projects. This will also be used for
syncing between PTL and Lieutenants during an office hours window.

Change-Id: I22748294669c6d402751448597c823f4bed66bbe
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 16170, 'date': '2015-06-05 21:21:35.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Start linuxbridge neutron agent using a launcher

This change ports linuxbridge neutron agent on common/service code
that will allow to handle termination signals (SIGHUP, SIGTERM, SIGINT).

Note that this patch allows changing only logging options.
All other config options are not handled explicitly and changing
them using SIGHUP can lead to unpredictable circumstances.
So, until changing other options is handled it is highly recommended
to use SIGHUP for changing ONLY logging options.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I1d834e0683b04111ef04c148cbd8d4acf2964065
Closes-Bug: #1461539

commit_message:
Use logging helper function in helper functions

The helper functions are intended to be simple batteries included entry
points. Complex applications, the type that might want to have an
opinion on logging, should really be creating an os_client_config object
and passing it in to the OpenStackCloud constructor anyway. SO - have
the simple functions consume the simple logging config.

Change-Id: I997a20c5a6ed73b76d0560ca73cdfd29b6b74682

commit_message:
Use graduated oslo.policy

- Add oslo.policy to requirements.txt
- Update Enforcer constructor to account for new config parameter
- Update policy_file references to account for new config section
- Remove in-tree copy of oslo.policy

Partial-Bug: #1458945
Change-Id: Ifad815a98d6d8efc9c84bd03cb31a40bbfeff948

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Make _val_to_py and _py_to_val not private

Move _val_to_py and _py_to_val to neutron.agent.ovsdb.api
and remove the underscore since they will be used by other
classes.

Change-Id: I3a469ab3b1c1d83ad20dc6c77f1072fc6d546419

commit_message:
Add resource_type filter parameter to Get property definition

Correct all filter parameter descriptions to make consistent
Fix some issues in os-metadata-object-v2.wadl
PUT method wasn't showing up
Parameter descriptions needed some clean-up

Change-Id: Ia05ce69f3eb19c6fbf57d1663291b503781679bb
Closes-Bug: #1378913

commit_message:
Use nagios-common instead of nagios-plugins-all on RHEL.

nagios-plugins-basic was mapped to nagios-plugins-all on RHEL, however
nagios-plugins-all is actually not shipped with RHEL. The reason it
seems to be installed via the snmpd element is so that the nagios
plugins directory exists.  This can be accomplished on RHEL by
installing nagios-common instead.

Migrates all of the element over to pkg-map as well for the other
installed packages.

Change-Id: I8773a93dcd8b348b501d8303ddd211b3edf1e2b9

commit_message:
Bump up Ceph job timeout for resource availability

The Ceph job seems to be hitting same timeout issues seen for HA
job: long waits during resources acquisition, see [1].

At [2] there is a sample case where CephStorage node never moved to
CREATE_COMPLETE, from CREATE_IN_PROGRESS, as timeout occurred sooner.

1. Change I72a5339a39fd7a447c37bec9f40ef08beb34d5f8
2. http://logs.openstack.org/62/187262/8/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-ceph/f00606e/console.html#_2015-06-03_18_42_42_322

Change-Id: I687c8305da6431aaf13f5708086e6a496f05c549

commit_message:
Enable udev for lvm in cinder-volume container

The current configuration of LVM for cinder-volume has udev_sync=0.
This means that udev is not creating the devices that appear in /dev.
The device files created reference specific device numbers, and these
persist between reboots. When the host is rebooted there is no
guarantee that device numbers allocated to the logical volumes will
match those defined in the device files. This can be observed by
comparing the output of 'dmsetup info' and 'ls -l /dev/mapper'.

LVM's use of udev was disabled in an attempt to protect the host from
the potential that uevents generated would be processed by all
containers on the host. In practise this should not be an issue because
there are not other containers running on a cinder host.

This commit adjusts the lvm.conf file created so that udev is used. It
also adds a mount entry to create a devtmpfs on /dev. Finally
'udevadm trigger' is run to add the devices under /dev/mapper.
Closes-Bug: #1436999
Change-Id: I9ab35cf4438a369563f8c08870c1acfd0cc394b0

commit_message:
Configure virtual IPs for split out networks

This patch optionally creates new virtual IPs for
the storage, storage_mgmt, and internal_api
networks if ip addresses are provided.

Additionally the HAproxy configuration is updated
to use hiera lookups to obtain virtual IPs for
alternate networks. By default the ctlplane
VIP is still used.

Change-Id: I20483574920a1da689374b0eb1b39b0391c3d243

commit_message:
Add interface_for_ip function

This patch adds a custom Puppet function called interface_for_ip
This function will be used within the TripleO puppet implementation
to help obtain the correct interface for a given IP address.

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ib09bf1a123c4fd1b88247539ab268c8385dc0faa

commit_message:
Stringify project details

There are some clouds that have things like integer project names.
That's no fun when they are interperted at int, so stringify them.
Stringifying integer project ids is apparently less important, but does
not hurt.

Change-Id: Ife9ecaa28c552d589dbea9a065da0dfa483592eb

When an image did not provide a build script, due to a broken link for
instance, the build-all-docker-images script was wrongly marking the
image as "up-to-date", and the functional gate was reporting success.

This commit restores the expected behavior, and mark the images with
non-existent build scripts as failures.

Closes-Bug: #1460959
'}]
commit_message:
Fail image build when build script is missing

When an image did not provide a build script, due to a broken link for
instance, the build-all-docker-images script was wrongly marking the
image as "up-to-date", and the functional gate was reporting success.

This commit restores the expected behavior, and mark the images with
non-existent build scripts as failures.

Change-Id: Ifedc8d9c312925fe5aa953ed8f8fdae02b756906
Closes-Bug: #1460959

commit_message:
Raise a warning with conflicting SSL params

Setting a cacert to check the cloud cert is useless when
changing the default verify flag to False since this will have
precedence. Raise a warning to alert the user about this
behavior.

Change-Id: I099d03fef5e8da0d6eed572613f4693604173ecd

This is another way to solve the problem of needing to test
anonymous function used in $watch. In my opinion, this requires

Instead, they need to simply name one of the functions which clearly

commit_message:
Flavor tests - Named functions for watch tests

This is another way to solve the problem of needing to test
anonymous function used in $watch. In my opinion, this requires
less boiler plate in the code under test, and is better than
requiring code writers to place the watch expression and watch
listener functions directly on the controller.

Instead, they need to simply name one of the functions which clearly
doesn't change the behavior, is still very readable, and allows the
Jasmine spy to find one of several calls to the same $watch in order
to pull out the watch expression and corresponding listener.

Change-Id: I0a7a03f20b3a3682a52da04045868dd1f7b09b20

The flavor tests exercise the anonymous functions passed to $watch. It
makes assumptions about the order that the code executes, which is hard
to maintain.

This is one way to fix the problem. Convert any anonymous functions that
need testing into functions available on the controller.

Change-Id: I851ae5cfafb424c979075a7d0240ba63688caa75
"}]
commit_message:
Flavor tests - Don't use anonymous functions that need testing

The flavor tests exercise the anonymous functions passed to $watch. It
makes assumptions about the order that the code executes, which is hard
to maintain.

This is one way to fix the problem. Convert any anonymous functions that
need testing into functions available on the controller.

Change-Id: I851ae5cfafb424c979075a7d0240ba63688caa75

commit_message:
Change references of "clouds.yaml" for real file

The config file clouds.yaml can be located in several places, and
even the file extension can be .yml. Replace all user visible
messages making reference for that file to show the full path
of the config file used.

Change-Id: I489d87368b72dfe69b7d4e3c07ba5d5249c45667

Well, my point is. Current default is 1000. Not many users will deploy 1000 resoruce template without nested templates. Nested templates were memory hit before we got them decoupled. Currently it isn't that much of a case. So this will prevent OOM errors only for stacks of 1000 resources in single non-nested stack, and frankly, if someone does, hes asking for troubles.

That being said, validation itself IS terribly memory-consuming thing. So if 99.5% people don't use 1000+ resource single stack, they'll go through validation anyway, and that might actually end up with OOM errors for bigger stacks. So is it worth it now, with decoupled nested?"}, {'account_id': 10787, 'date': '2015-05-28 12:42:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Without a limit any user can, with little more than a ~15 line template, create the HOT equivalent of a fork bomb that will take down Heat, even if it is deployed at arbitrary scale.

commit_message:
Unlimited option max_resources_per_stack

Since biggest issue for memory problems is nested stack max
resources validation, this patch creates option to remove limit
which skips whole validation whatsoever.

Change-Id: I7c851fcad2d4a41b2f9df42244862b04304812b0
Partial-Bug: #1455589

commit_message:
Handle SIGHUP in ovs neutron agent

This change allows ovs neutron agent not to die on receiving SIGHUP
and reload its logging options.

Note that this patch allows changing only logging options.
All other config options are not handled explicitly and changing
them using SIGHUP can lead to unpredictable circumstances.
So, until changing other options is handled it is highly recommended
to use SIGHUP for changing ONLY logging options.

Change-Id: Ic0cf8a9ca7f3a16b556a6825e2979471ae136c33
Partial-Bug: #1276694

commit_message:
devstack: Stop hacking blessed into global-requirements

Forgot this in the last devstack patch.

This stops having devstack add blessed to openstack global-requirements.

Also, this renames BUILD_AKANDA_DEV_APPLIANCE to the more intuitive
BUILD_AKANDA_APPLIANCE_IMAGE.

Change-Id: Ic69018e45d103a383daf17ef7c82b8f727554d21

commit_message:
Return provider_id in SolidFire model update

The provider_id field was added in
commit: 9f34d34d0ab92400223e3cc87285d0d4fbdf21f9

This patch adds provider_id to the returned model
update and uses it to provide the internal SolidFire
volume ID mapping.

Next step will be to rewrite the awkward list search
of volume names to find the corresponding volume on
the SolidFire backend.

Change-Id: Ia44d46362bb1b688c4ac266afecca9ce66dcef25

commit_message:
Fix cloud-init Python syntax for Python < 2.6

The loguserdata.py file gets uploaded to the servers created by Heat to run
under cloud-init. Since the default versions of Python installed on the
user's server may be very old (e.g. RHEL 5 defaults to Python 2.4), avoid
using the octal syntax introduced for Python 3.0 and backported only as far
as Python 2.6. (Also avoid the old syntax, which will break on Python 3.x.)

Also remove use of the "with" statement from loguserdata.py and
part-handler.py. This statement is only available from Python 2.6 on (or in
Python 2.5 via "from __future__ import with_statement").

Finally, remove use of the "except ExceptionType as value" syntax for
catching exceptions. Again, this was only backported to Python 2.6.

Change-Id: I89e86d00993d51e2514b1e589503c6d966909403
Partial-Bug: #1375864

go: new tmp dir layout

This change is being discussed for python swift - use 00-FF directories
underneath per-drive tmp to better distribute files among XFS allocation
groups.

commit_message:
Multiple pools support enhancement in VNX cinder driver

This introduced a new option "storage_vnx_pool_names" which
replaced the existing option "storage_vnx_pool_name". The new option
allows user specify more than one pools to be managed by a vnx
cinder back end.

DocImpact
This change will introduce a new configuration option, so that the
documentation need to be updated.

Change-Id: Id6c3a1ecb32484fbd35dbb5814262103b322249e
Closes-Bug: 1456062

commit_message:
Fix NullPointerExceptions in MetricFilteringBolt

This happened because MetricDefinitionAndTenantIdMatcher wasn't handling
the same Alarm Definition being added. This happens because there are
multiple MetricFilteringBolts using the same
MetricDefinitionAndTenantIdMatcher. The Alarm Definition is now
checked if is already there before being added

Change-Id: I9f382e8da5193b60a64dbe40c9fcf321fc47766f

commit_message:
Decompose db_base_plugin_v2.py

Moved private getters and simple helpers into db_base_plugin_common.
This change is part of bigger refactoring for supporting Pluggable IPAM.
Main purpose is to make getters accessible by IPAM code.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I1eac61c258541bca80e14be4b7c75519a014ffae

commit_message:
Add waiting for keystone to be fully available after haproxy restart

Sometimes keystone is not available right after haproxy restart. To
consider that in the tests preliminary check of the situation added in
form of ostf sanity set execution.

Change-Id: I4a5d6adcc13ca1e996e0ed6bdbaa0ef35352f4b9
Partial-Bug: #1446590

commit_message:
Don't update floating IP status if no change

The floating IP status was going through all of the
status update code every time the L3 agent sent in
an update, even if the status didn't change.

This patch skips sending updates to the server if the
agent doesn't change the status.

Change-Id: Ic3736bed3dc3e4ccb91f4acfabbf033949e09ce0
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit c44506bfd60b2dd6036e113464f1ea682cfaeb6c)

commit_message:
Fix delayed activation without disk and containers formats

If we want to perform a delayed activation of an image without
providing disk format or container format, Glance tries to
upload a file and fails with 400 error.

This code handles this situation by checking that no sources
were provided, and returns information about the image before
starting the upload.

Change-Id: Id6f81df9bb43697b0d694528b010bb3c7c9bedb3
Closes-Bug: #1268680

commit_message:
Add clock skew status checking

  Remove redundant 'get_ceph_health' function.
  Remove unused 'get_status' function.
  Make 'get_osd_tree' and 'get_osd_id' invoke 'run_on_remote' helper function.
  Add clock skew status checking to 'get_node_fqdns_w_clock_skew'.

Change-Id: I1db0a90233ab0e3395778f5e25869dd2a8d997b8
Closes-bug: #1462217

commit_message:
Fix password $-escaping in cobbler kickstart templates

Cobbler uses Cheetah rendering engine which treats $ as template
sign. All non-related to templating $ should be escaped.

Non-escaped $ leads to templating failure in cobbler which triggers
dnsmasq restart. Multiple dnsmasq restarts in a short period of time
could lead to harmful dns resolition failure during OS installation.

In order to fix templating failures, all exposed passwords should be
surrounded by 'raw escaping' block.

Eg.:
 #raw
 foo = $foo
 #end raw

Change-Id: Id16646ed1e19fce71931235aae67227c0a7433da
Related-Bug: 1458533

commit_message:
Rewrite yum in kickstart to do retries on failures

This commit makes yum run in installation retry
up to 10 times in case of failures making
classic provisioning for CentOS more tolerant
do DNS and repo connectivity failures

Change-Id: Ibc450de102c0f76b10c945ada4c35dd6845969ef
Partial-bug: 1458533

commit_message:
Make extensions configurable

Depending on the MidoNet version, different set of extensions may be
supported.  In addition to the common extensions supported by all the
MidoNet versions (`supported_extension_aliases`), allow users to
configure additional extensions in the configuration file based on the
MidoNet support.

Co-Authored-By: Ryu Ishimoto <ryu@midokura.com>

Change-Id: I867f60ab243370ed530035222e798f7b57ea64ed
Fixes: MNP-124

commit_message:
fix wrong title for OS-INHERIT Extension spec

The title of API "DELETE /OS-INHERIT/projects/{project_id)/groups/{gro-
up_id}/roles/{role_id}/inherited_to_projects" was "Revoke an inherited
project role from group on domain", it should be "Revoke an inherited
project role from group on project".

Change-Id: Ic79aec003ec68e81126151c1983966fb612ff68b
Closes-Bug: #1462355

commit_message:
Fix some issues in devref for api_microversions

- The spec is now implemented instead of approved.
- The samples should pass the pep8 test.
- Make sample code use consistent variable names.
- Add a note about which tests may need updates when creating a new
  microversion.

Change-Id: I6796b7e055322647e2cae2d993d79a4b1cacc70c

commit_message:
Fix list of type_drivers for ML2 plugin

The list of drivers loaded by the ML2 plugin does not have to
match the list of tenant_network_types, this will make ML2 load
the flat, gre, vxlan and vlan drivers so that the provider
networks can be of flat (default) and vlan type as well.

Change-Id: I0b74f86acf5c1ff644deb46c0a1d14129c1882d4

commit_message:
Wire Neutron VLAN ranges param as array to puppet

Turns NeutronNetworkVLANRanges into a list and makes it consumable by
neutron::plugins::ml2::network_vlan_ranges as an array. Previously
usage of vlans was impossible due to puppet-neutron failing to
join() network_vlan_ranges.

Also fixes wiring of network_vlan_ranges on computes and adds a
sample environment file to test use of vlans for tenant networks.

Change-Id: I8725cdb9591dd8d0b7125fdacbefdc9138703266

commit_message:
Add support_status to all resources in contrib

This change adds support_status to all the resources that are in the
contrib area of the repository that don't have it already. These resources are
given the UNSUPPORTED status, to indicate that the Heat team is not responsible
for maintaining them.

Change-Id: I8835bf3f99774c40da1e8d34a474071a71686cd1

commit_message:
Integrate PD Reference Implementation with neutron db/agent

This patch implements IPv6 Prefix Delegation for automatic allocation
of subnet CIDRs in Neutron. This allows automatic allocation of IPv6
subnet prefixes to be offloaded to an external DHCPv6 prefix
delegation server maintained by the OpenStack deployer.

To enable this feature, subnets have been given a new property,
ipv6_pd_enabled. This property is hidden and does not affect the Neutron API.

WORKFLOW:

1. Admin sets default_ipv6_subnet_pool in neutron.conf to "prefix_delegation"
2. User creates a new IPv6 subnet without a CIDR or subnetpool ID
3. User creates an interface between this subnet and a router with an existing
external interface

A patch for admin/user documentation is up for review here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178739

Video guides for configuring and using this feature are available on
YouTube:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wI830s881HQ
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zfsFyS01Fn0

Change-Id: Ib681b9a2a509b5c2883111251b20082f6442e2ed
Co-Authored-By: Baodong (Robert) Li <baoli@cisco.com>
Implements: blueprint ipv6-prefix-delegation

commit_message:
Add provider extension support

Adds support for the 'provider:network_type' field in network
creation. This is included in the 'provider' extension.

Other fields included in this extension (segmentation_id and physical_network)
are not supported.

The only value allowed for 'provider:network_type' is 'local'.

This means that the user is allowed to specify that a network with the
fields 'provider:network_type':'local' if he chooses. This information
is then given to the midonet backend so that the backend can treat
this network as a 'provider network', which is described in specs/provider_net.

Implements: specs/provider_net
Change-Id: I475388612a941b6511da1781bca2971270052abb
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>
Fixes: MNP-73

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-05 14:51:08.000000000', 'message': 'Added pseudo param OS::tenant_id

tenant id can be used to identify or tag who created the resources. The
tenant id can be found in cfn psedo param AWS::StackId, but when we

commit_message:
Added pseudo param OS::project_id

project id can be used to identify or tag which project the resources
belong to. The project id can be found in cfn pseudo param AWS::StackId, but when we
switch to hot, OS::stack_id is a pure stack id, no project info in it. So
we add OS::project_id to meet the similar scenario requirements.

Change-Id: I3db9db7c59cfa0ff3005a97cd0cb7962928598ab

commit_message:
Adding a new script  to generate mkek and hmac

Shuffled a few items out of the pkcs11 module to allow
it to continue working as normal but also account for the
generation of mkek and hmac.

Change-Id: I811e9a8498087c33d8a59e85d71200e7eb27ae58

commit_message:
libvirt: make _create_domain return a Guest object

Updates libvirt driver to return a Guest object after calling
the method _create_domain.

Change-Id: Ie690e88fb4dcfcd468c2fd616fb2e0734e517f1d

commit_message:
Handle FlavorNotFound when augmenting migrated flavors

When we migrate a partial flavor from system_metadata to a full
flavor in instance_extra, we need to query for the original flavor in
order to fill in the missing extra_specs. If that fails because the
flavor has been deleted, we need to just not augment the flavor, log
a warning, and continue instead of failing.

Change-Id: Ida49ddea525fb54e0d0238746b83b0202da437c3
Related-Bug: #1460673

commit_message:
Moved all of group_vars into a variable file

Moved all of the group_vars/all.yml file into its own variable file
This change was done to allow a user to override basic options
without having to modify the default group variable files. While
the group_vars/all.yml file is still present it is only holding the
revision information that is used for release data and the minimal
required kernel that allows the system to function using VXLAN.

The upgrade script was modified to support the new "default"
user_group_vars.yml file.

tempest_swift_enabled was set to true in group_vars, so this has
now been set as a default in the role instead.

Commit 1bd2bc052a36c7f8c28e473d0a37fd29827198b0 implemented the
package URL update for rabbitmq, but not the corresponding sha256
update. This was not noticed due to group_vars overriding the URL
to a previous version, resulting in the above-mentioned commit
taking no effect. This patch therefore also corrects the sha256.

Conflicts:
        playbooks/inventory/group_vars/all.yml

Closes-Bug: #1460516
Closes-Bug: #1460992
Change-Id: I8e42bb124827bb276134d662c9a171db8e4c017e

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method to delete domain config

Adds method delete_configuration to the Guest object
and updates the libvirt driver code to use it.

Change-Id: Ic4709edf0a8f91bcd6219f2da96f50d3ab1df54d

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method to get vcpus info

Adds method get_vcpus_info to the Guest object and updates
the libvirt driver code to use it.
It returns vcpus information of a guest as a structure
GuestVCPUInfo

Change-Id: Id96629e52dd04463d04b0853d9e300f31426ccb1

subject: libvirt: introduce method resume to Guest object

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method resume to Guest object

Adds method resume to the Guest object and updates the
libvirt driver code to use it.
Also updates methods _attach_pci_devices and
_attach_sriov_ports to use a Guest object.

Change-Id: Id28eb6014cc1751a00dfcd94f430b29f75061978

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method poweroff to Guest object

Adds method poweroff to the Guest object and updates
the libvirt driver code to use it.

Change-Id: I95399d7efd03d66cee847068db78d2993d7a88b0

commit_message:
Use node IP lists for HA Proxy ipaddresses

This patch updates the loadbalancer class so that it
defaults to trying to use the node IP list for each
respective service. This data is provided via Hiera
directly (all-nodes-config provides it via the Heat
templates).

By default the ctlplane IP address list is still used
if no service node IP list is provided.

Change-Id: I34cbdf8bd525e6ab61859fe8b8c18fe613dabbfe

commit_message:
Fix configuration of the Elastcisearch plugin

This change fixes the attributes passed to Nailgun when deploying the
Elastcisearch-Kibana plugin. The attribute names missed the '/value'
suffix which was breaking the Fuel UI but it didn't fail on the Astute
part.

Change-Id: I8d889ce1ace9c7dd817e2a4646887fd2c45f9cfb

commit_message:
Fix configuration of the LMA collector plugin

This change fixes the attributes passed to Nailgun when deploying the
LMA collector plugin and its associated plugins. The attribute names
missed the '/value' suffix which was breaking the Fuel UI but it didn't
fail on the Astute part.

Change-Id: I3616165382e9b11e63c01c915b2f720c5c1eaed9

commit_message:
Allow the Horizon SESSION_TIMEOUT to be configured

This will only configure the variable if the horizon_session_timeout
user variable is defined.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1461623
Change-Id: Idd9eb58651f6e45bfdb5a65c2529c2e2f0b45f09
(cherry picked from commit 74e6a42257a856f40b4f52e446e32aa9bfcbebb4)

commit_message:
Support standalone ironic

Add two options in this patch to support standalone ironic without
keystone services.

*auth_strategy
*ironic_url

Change-Id: Iffa50a40971264aacc97f7210aa227a6655eaf42
Closes-bug: 1459471

commit_message:
Raise a warning when using 'cloud' in config

The former use of 'cloud' in the config file, was changed
in favor of 'profile' to avoid confusions.

Change-Id: Iba08746a06ebb397ee1d0f59d5cda41db2b86053

commit_message:
Add cloud vendor files config in doc

Although it is possible to include specific config files for
unknown vendors, this wasn't specified in the documentation.

Change-Id: Ib27277d480e373a8a083e820161e0bdb985de284

Blocking it for now. This patch may open up a security hole. Service user is neither Keystone admin or server admin and they should not have list user privileges. When creating a trust, it is up to the trustor to obtain the user ID from the trustee discretely.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-05-28 06:40:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@guang-yee, thanks for the review.

One workaround is to have user specify service user ID in service configuration file. That would be very inconvenient. It means you have to make sure service user is created before generating the conf file. Using user name in conf file would be more convenient.

Another way to describe the problem. A service user wants to get its own user ID, so that the service requester can use it. Don't see any security breach here. Am I missing something?"}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-05-28 15:54:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'd be more inclined allow users to lookup their own ID. That's part of self-service. But we should not allow service user to list all users. The changes would be similar to this one

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164848/

btw, this may only work if you are using the V3 APIs. Also, we should enhance our V3Password auth plugin to take username/domain instead of just user_id."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-05-28 22:52:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"allow users to lookup their own ID" is already very helpful. The user case is exactly letting service user to find out his own user ID.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-05-29 00:24:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Allow a user to get his own user information

This patch enables a user to get user info about himself. The usage
scenario is for a user to get his own user ID (for example) when in
program only the user name is known.

Closes-Bug: 1459482
Change-Id: I14d6bc529a1d484b7b7fa9e0a9466b99957e84a7

commit_message:
Deprecate the HPLeftHandISCSIDriver CLIQ driver

This patch adds a deprecation message to the HPLeftHandISCSIDriver CLIQ
driver with the plan of removing it in the 2016.1 release. The
HPLeftHandISCSIDriver REST based driver should be used instead.

Change-Id: I9eb1fc71d7be4848f116e0585964af97cae210b5

commit_message:
Add a non-mixin function for model queries

This patch simply adds a version of model_query in
neutron.db.common_db_mixin which can be invoked without
having to declare a class which inherits the mixin.

To this aim, model_query_scope has been refactored as well.
As the model query function being introduced in this patch
cannot use model query hooks (and does not need to), the
method was re-implemented rather than bringing out of the
mixin as it has been done for model_query_scope.

This change will allow for developing DB APIs without
having to use the baseDB/mixin classes models used so far.

Related-Blueprint: better-quotas

Change-Id: I7a79980f626e9eaf2775711c8a25f508067e5716

commit_message:
Select proper release ID when updating defaults

fuel-package-updates now searches for release ID
that matches version and operating_system of a
release in Nailgun.

Fixed spelling of mos-updates repo to match default.

Change-Id: I1e5b54290b44f40dcf13badb737565ee5ce2114a
Closes-Bug: #1461546

commit_message:
Do not pass rich objects on server's resume

Unit tests for "immediate resume" were removed as they no longer differ
in principle from "wait resume" tests due to an extra API call
introduced.

Partial-Bug: #1393268
Change-Id: I291bd6c33634727f17c64646f776c0777ce3939c

commit_message:
Fix service order for galera check xinetd

Otherwise galeracheck will not work if /etc/services
is not edited before xinetd service is declared

Change-Id: Ia336f722e8e9f8aa6e6d25cc7e5bed9081d02c39
Related-bug: #1462142

Because some of the packages (python-cinderclient, keystonemiddleware)
do not release new versions with pbr requirements aligned with
OpenStack global requirements, we have a conflict in requirements
since new packages install pbr 1.0.1 (newest one) and "old" packages

commit_message:
Set upper bounds of packages using old pbr

Because some of the packages (python-cinderclient, keystonemiddleware)
do not release new versions with pbr requirements aligned with
OpenStack global requirements, we have a conflict in requirements
since new packages install pbr 1.0.1 (newest one) and "old" packages
want pbr<=1.0.
Because of that we limit higher version of explicitly installed packages
so we avoid this issue.

Change-Id: If90e0795cf8cebdeb381b17ad0a694b7b35f3d88
Closes-Bug: #1461980

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-04 13:43:01.000000000', 'message': 'Set run_as_root to True by default in NetcatTester

Because of NetcatTester consumes namespaces which are not root namespace
it makes more sense to use root by default.

Change-Id: If042efcd75e46b66abf4a9e303e633749a1611b1
'}, {'created': '2015-06-04 14:17:06.000000000', 'message': "Run netcat always as root in NetcatTester

As currently we always use NetcatTester in a namespace and there is no
use case to run it in root namespace, we should always spawn 'nc'
process under root permissions.

Change-Id: If042efcd75e46b66abf4a9e303e633749a1611b1
"}, {'created': '2015-06-04 14:38:54.000000000', 'message': "Run RootHelperProcess always as root

The purpose of RootHelperProcess is to spawn processes running with root
id. Instantiating RootHelperProcess as non-root doesn't make sense. This
also implies NetcatTester always spawns 'netcat' process as root. The
reason why parameter existed here was due to refactor from passing
root_helper all over the place.

Change-Id: If042efcd75e46b66abf4a9e303e633749a1611b1
"}]
commit_message:
Run RootHelperProcess always as root

The purpose of RootHelperProcess is to spawn processes running with root
id. Instantiating RootHelperProcess as non-root doesn't make sense. This
also implies NetcatTester always spawns 'netcat' process as root. The
reason why parameter existed here was due to refactor from passing
root_helper all over the place.

Change-Id: If042efcd75e46b66abf4a9e303e633749a1611b1

commit_message:
Authenticate scenario unit test improvements

This makes several improvements to the unit tests for the Authenticate
scenario:

* Unit tests were in two files; one test was duplicated. They are
  combined into a single file that is the same predictable place as
  the other scenario unit tests.
* Mocking of the Scenario.clients function is made consistent with the
  other scenario unit tests.
* Other misc. cleanup.

Change-Id: Iaa86ef514534ada00e868be564f0b6acd6b11ff1

commit_message:
Create initiator id for VMAX iSCSI driver

This is related to Bug #1440427. The fix for that bug only addressed
the issue for the FC driver. The same problem exists for the iSCSI
driver. This patch addressed the problem for the VMAX iSCSI driver.
The initiator id will be created on the array if it does not exist
for the iSCSI driver.

Change-Id: I5df57df122a704066d4d7a1997ac2642b073c9e8
Closes-Bug: #1446443
(cherry picked from commit c94e6b153a424056c846f7ba19ee617650174282)

to the code as well.

commit_message:
Remove redandunt build-in functions

There are some redandunt build-in functions 'side_effect'
in test_remote_stack.py.
According the docs:
https://docs.python.org/3/library/unittest.mock.html#unittest.mock.Mock.side_effect
The 'side_effect' can either be a function
to be called when the mock is called, an iterable
or an exception (class or instance) to be raised.

Change-Id: I0ea5f64865c04f959df2ec144ab235a8c3503a8b

sqlalchemy: use JSON from sqlalchemy-utils

Rather than implementing our own, let's use the one in sqlalchemy-utils.

Change-Id: I7ec9362396b0235916e97e67cb1655432c43769f

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Register oslo_log options before using them

Launching this test alone will fail otherwise as we use conf.debug and
it's not registered.

Change-Id: I39392d3b9e369c84342580bbffd6b15435fe820e

commit_message:
Remove rsdns directory

The rsdns service is no longer needed since trove now supports designate.
It is not being tested in the gate and is currently unsupported.

Remove other rsdns related files and references.

Change-Id: I44009dace44afb5467c51def33c794641ffa33c0
Closes-Bug: #1454028

commit_message:
Adding some more constraints to cron trigger

 * User was able to create some triggers
   with different names but the same first-time
   and count. Now it is fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1449514

Change-Id: Ifde94b2f183faad8c9a5bb8723f11945da5bc08a

[{'created': '2015-04-22 20:55:16.000000000', 'message': 'Enable Heat SSL support

The referenced bug in Heat has been fixed, so we can go ahead and
register the endpoint for https.

Also, this was buggy before anyway.  We were registering a non-ssl
port with an https prefix.

A comparable change will be proposed for os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: I490a65f0c64bcf2529a393364447f2cb9318598a
'}]
commit_message:
Enable Heat SSL support

The referenced bug in Heat has been fixed, so we can go ahead and
register the endpoint for https.

Also, this was buggy before anyway.  We were registering a non-ssl
port with an https prefix.

A comparable change will be proposed for os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: I490a65f0c64bcf2529a393364447f2cb9318598a

[{'created': '2015-06-03 15:03:21.000000000', 'message': 'Fix capacity filter to allow oversubscription

Currently the capacity filter does not allow oversubscrition
if the free physical capacity is less than the new volume size.
This was based on the assumption that a new thinly provisioned
volume will be consumed right away. This assumption does not
allow us to take full advantage of thin provisioning.
