commit_message:
Fix capacity filter to allow oversubscription

Currently the capacity filter does not allow oversubscrition
if the free physical capacity is less than the new volume size.
This was based on the assumption that a new thinly provisioned
volume will be consumed right away. This assumption does not
allow us to take full advantage of thin provisioning.

The fix is to allow oversubscription if thin provisioning is
supported and max_over_subscription_ratio is greater than or
equal to 1. The free physical capacity will not be used to
compare with the new volume size for a backend that supports
oversubscription in thin provisioning. The oversubscription
ratio and virtual free capacity will still be used to decide
whether a backend can be chosen for thin provisioning.

Closes-Bug: #1458976
Change-Id: I4c8904445654db839c25ded420915f83c3756f94
(cherry picked from commit 75953752e41819b0d2ca770d4d13ed1ccaec685a)

commit_message:
Fix incorrect status update during upload in v2

If the image is deleted (i.e. its status changed to 'deleted' in db)
when it's uploading through image-upload command in v2, its status
surprisingly switches from 'deleted' to 'active' without any exception.

The existed code improves original StateTrackingObject by saving all
changed values (including Status) and prevents incorrect status update
by passing from_state argument like it's done in v1.
If the situation occurs an exception is raised, then it is processed
and image file is safely removed.

Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <ian.cordasco@rackspace.com>
Closes-Bug: 1372564
Change-Id: I3225ef7aeb8baec6f30e605f6d5d5da77429e9c8

commit_message:
Add functional test job for ceilometer

We have a functional tests for ceilometer and
current patch adds the job to project-config to configure and
these tests.

Put it to experimental jobs to make sure of correct working.

Change-Id: I2714a145bece0da86d3a50f313d74535fd2c8607
Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-functional-tests

commit_message:
Updates examples to reference new sample format

The list function for the new Sample Manager no longer takes a
meter_name parameter. It must be submitted as part of the query.
The changes reflect the new format.

Change-Id: I2c9346ce605b3f576a761f6162a5dcf49e4686ee
Closes-Bug:1443383

Modify heading of the template sample page

Currently the headings for Hello World HOT template
and AWS Wordpress Single Instance Template pages is
"Template". This patch modifies the heading
of these pages.

commit_message:
Add ha test case with assigning public network to all nodes.

- add deploy_ha_with_pub_net_all_nodes test case to Contrail Plugin test folder;
- modify prepare_contrail_plugin and assign_net_provider methods for
deploy_ha_with_pub_net_all_node test case.

Closes-Bug: #1461989

commit_message:
Allow to fail instead of skip in DbFixture

Tests using DbFixture[1] are currently skipped if the database is
unavailable (no db service, no permissions, etc.) which is fine when
tests are runned by developers but not when runned by the gate jobs.

This change defines the attribute DbFixture.SKIP_ON_UNAVAILABLE_DB: when
the database is unvailable, tests are:

* skipped when SKIP_ON_UNAVAILABLE_DB=True (default, legacy behaviour),
* failed when SKIP_ON_UNAVAILABLE_DB=False.

[1] oslo.db.sqlalchemy.test_base

Change-Id: I067f46417fefe252c650e1e5e590e83547b11b6a
Closes-Bug: #1404093

commit_message:
Allow provisioning to reach max oversubscription

Currently if provisioned ratio is equal to max_over_subscription_ratio,
the capacity filter does not allow any more thin provisioning. This patch
makes a change so that thin provisioning is allowed if provisioned ratio
is equal to max_over_subscription_ratio; it will only stop provisioning
if provisioned ratio is greater than max_over_subscription_ratio.

Change-Id: Ibf13ef97472b80a1b59ffd4389a4ed2eacf67205
Partial-Bug: #1458976

http://specs.openstack.org/openstack-infra/infra-specs/specs/puppet-modules.html'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:25:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Openstack providing anything that looks like official support for a driver that was removed from cinder for not being properly supported is, to my mind, doing an end-run around the cinder community standards. We're happy to have it back in once it meets those standards (in particular, CI)... until then, there's nothing stopping anybody hosting it in a github tree themselves, it doesn't need to be stackforge."}, {'account_id': 2376, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Mike I agree it is not supported by HP and it is a bit the problem. We have developped that driver by ourself with access to this kind of array (thanks to HP), and we have been asking HP to give us that kind of access again so that we can setup the proper CI... We are strugglig with that for almost a year now... and without any success.

@Duncan as far as I know stackforge is for any project related to OpenStack, without regards to the "quality" of them... In that case we have a driver that was godd enought to be in the cinder trunk for 2 years and has been removed due to a new (good) policy. So I think the quality has been "proved" to be as good as many stackforge project...'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-04-20 07:11:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

If we're going to be instructing people to install this driver to a Cinder installation from something like stackforge, that might not work just because the driver isn't being tested continuously. If we can see a CI working with this driver, I don't understand why we can't just propose this back to Cinder again. This stackforge thing doesn't make sense to me."}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-04-20 13:52:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-05 10:15:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I see that ship has sailed now, but I don't see why this should have been rejected. Stackforge is pretty much for "everything else", so I think it's fine for drivers without CI to live there.'}]

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

[{'created': '2014-08-21 18:48:15.000000000', 'message': 'Python sessions, streaming, and increased pool

Since glance started using python-swiftclient 2.0.8 it has been seeing
WARNING requests.packages.urllib3.connectionpool [-] HttpConnectionPool
is full, discarding connection: messages.

The pool (a LifoQueue) is configured to be quite small by default. When
a connection is requested using a pool, a connection is taken from the
pool. If there are no connections in the pool, a new connection is
created (unless blocking is enabled). When the user is done with the
connection, it is put back into the queue. If the queue is already full,
it is discarded, and an "HttpConnectionPool is full, discarding
connection" message is generated. When the queue is too small, many new
connections will be created and because the pool can fill and empty so
quickly many of the connections will be discarded.

Special care has to be taken with streams. Since streams don't download
all of the data at once, if all the data is not read, the connection
must be explicitly freed.

This patch makes fixes for Python Request streams and the pool size.

Change-Id: I53e6ae9c316d64267fde769586eaf5ae2791e7d8
Closes-Bug: 1295812

commit_message:
Python sessions, streaming, and increased pool

Since glance started using python-swiftclient 2.0.8 it has been seeing
WARNING requests.packages.urllib3.connectionpool [-] HttpConnectionPool
is full, discarding connection: messages.

The pool (a LifoQueue) is configured to be quite small by default. When
a connection is requested using a pool, a connection is taken from the
pool. If there are no connections in the pool, a new connection is
created (unless blocking is enabled). When the user is done with the
connection, it is put back into the queue. If the queue is already full,
it is discarded, and an "HttpConnectionPool is full, discarding
connection" message is generated. When the queue is too small, many new
connections will be created and because the pool can fill and empty so
quickly many of the connections will be discarded.

Special care has to be taken with streams. Since streams don't download
all of the data at once, if all the data is not read, the connection
must be explicitly freed.

This patch updates the pool size and enables streams only for get and
put object by default and makes them user configurable.

Change-Id: I53e6ae9c316d64267fde769586eaf5ae2791e7d8
Closes-Bug: 1295812

Fix exit code

When swift is in error, exit status is not good because shell script is not waiting that thread finished

commit_message:
SwiftClient object beginning with / or ./

Currently the SwiftClient Upload code removes the / or ./ in an object path
after creating dictionary response. This checkin fixes the ordering of this
update and adds a functional test to verify this behavior.

Change-Id: I2f818e6a66efab4ae453a230d45166f7b0e8ac3e
Closes-Bug: 1412425

commit_message:
New cipher module based on AES/CBC

This cipher module is intended to replace the Fernet based encryption.
The advantage of this implementation is that it allows the keys used to
be customizable.

Change-Id: Id788ea90fd9bcd571b41e65694c3b148251c5f11

commit_message:
Forbid deleting profiles in use

This patch adds detection that a profile is referenced by some clusters
or some nodes. We don't allow deleting such profiles. User can do a
cluster-list or node-list with filters to find out which cluster/node is
causing problem, so we don't response with the referencing entity here.

Another tweaking is to the middleware fault module. We list exception
types in name order.

Change-Id: I72c73bae22d6ec7b819c3af5657fe3635aeecf41

commit_message:
Sync oslo packages

This patch resync openstack common packages with oslo.incubator. It also
deleteds the fileutils module which is not used.

commit_message:
Do not pass rich objects in server's suspend

Unit tests for "immediate suspend" were removed as they no longer differ
in principle from "wait suspend" tests due to an extra API call
introduced.

Change-Id: I2f42c664742b208f68364dca8040990c0aa01b19
Partial-Bug: #1393268

commit_message:
Isolate the Ceph storage and storage_mgmt nets

This patch updates the Ceph configuration for the puppet
implementation so that it isolates the Ceph traffic
for the public and cluster interfaces. By default public traffic
runs on the "storage" network and the cluster traffic runs on the
"storage mgmt" network.

If network isolation is not enabled then the default
ctlplane address's will be used for both the public and
cluster interfaces.

Change-Id: I791244d72c8f42142d9de99e0cf0acdca19e62b0

commit_message:
Refactored the doc subtree

We need to start working on some introductory materials for the project
and service. We may also need to document our thoughts and design
decisions when moving forward. This patch tries to provide a basic
layout of the documents.

commit_message:
Introduce abstract base class for services

Service object that is passed to any launcher must implement
the following methods:
    * start
    * stop
    * wait
    * reset

Introducing abstract base class from which all openstack
services that use common.service code can subclass guarantees it.

Added documentation for launcher classes in service.py

Change-Id: Ibb5bc812de92629797619c8f95253addb46927fe
Closes-Bug: #1447965

user variable is defined.

[{'created': '2015-05-27 13:56:20.000000000', 'message': 'IBP: disable mcollective automatically starting for ubuntu

By default mcollective will be started automatically.
If it will be started prior cloud-init and nailgun-agent,
multiple instances of mcollective service could be started with
different server.cfg settings applied.

This patch disables automatically starting of mcollective during
the process of image building. Later, cloud-init will remove this
lock to allow mcollective to be started automatically.

Change-Id: Ibe5c41b1bb5bbf395fff14da281c4b08701c01b8
Closes-Bug: #1458623

commit_message:
IBP: disable mcollective automatically starting for ubuntu

By default mcollective will be started automatically.
If it will be started prior cloud-init and nailgun-agent,
multiple instances of mcollective service could be started with
different server.cfg settings applied.

This patch disables automatically starting of mcollective during
the process of image building. Later, cloud-init will remove this
lock to allow mcollective to be started automatically.

Change-Id: Ibe5c41b1bb5bbf395fff14da281c4b08701c01b8
Related-Bug: #1458623

commit_message:
Handle SIGTERM in linuxbridge_neutron_agent

This change allows linuxbridge_neutron_agent to gracefully exit
daemon loop on receiving SIGTERM while setting timeout for new rpc
calls received afterwards.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3b7344c7e0facd2ed2c00a3312c9fea7211dc674
Closes-Bug: #1461539

I like the specificity and simplicity here. Of course this is much less ambitious than Eugene's proposal - especially as flavors are admin-only for creation."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-06-26 10:34:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(11 comments)

Thanks for posting the spec, Mark.

Basically I don't see how this proposal is simpler in usage or implementation.

Specific issues I see in the proposal:

 1. API and data model are in fact more complex than Flavors/tags.
API/object model have more attributes, the workflow is more complex for the operators,
while users have less descriptive flavors.
 2. The idea of pushing drivers entry points via API with whole configuration
is questionable.
 3. Configuration pushed via API - is not very handy in usage.
Admins will have to write extensive CLI command to push such configuration.
To make this actually usable - we'll have to provide more structured API to that.
For sure that is out of scope of flavors, but still is important to make this usable.
 4. Nothing was said about validation of such configurations - looks like it should be driver's responsibility.
 5. The proposal in current form gives no space for the drivers to implement their own scheduling to actual backend.
In fact, the proposal only suggests choosing the implementation.
 6. The idea of extension list is also questionable as there's need to have more fine-grained specification of supported API aspects. I think most of production-ready drivers will support all of the service APIs, but may not support every aspects of those APIs, and there's no way for the user to discover the differences.

Another important thing is that proposed use cases could be implemented easily with an alternative approach.
The actual workflow will differ, however, it is, in my opinion, simpler.

The most notable difference is that while CRUDing flavors can be done via REST API, driver configuration is really an offline operation, e.g. it should be done at the point of deployment or in maintenance windows, just like every reconfiguration is done right now.

I don't think introducing dynamic configuration in the scope of flavors is a right way to go."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-06-26 10:37:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Btw, I'm not at all opposed to the idea of dynamically configuring drivers, but this problem in itself is not simple and I would not add it do the original problem of service instance specification."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:16:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Reading through the new spec (and the old one again) and putting aside the methods for accessing new resources for the moment I see a couple of differences. (The first one being the more significant difference.) Listing them here to see if I understand the proposals correctly. I am sure I will be corrected if this is not accurate.

1-  In Eugene's proposal, a flavor is matched with a driver while in Mark's proposal a Flavor is matched with a service profile which is essentially a two-tuple: (driver, metadata). 
In Eugene's proposal once the match is done, there is no specialization of how the driver is used and what sets of services/capabilities it provides. When you get the driver, you get the driver. 

2- In Mark's proposal, the association between service profiles and flavors are to be made explicitly. You have to associate a service profile with a flavor. In Eugene's proposal, the association happens implicitly (automatically, when needed) based on matching capabilities."}, {'account_id': 1923, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:57:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I would also add a 3rd difference which is more of a philosophical difference but admins and operators should be able to chime in and say which one is more useful in practice.

3- The difference is the level of granularity with which capabilities are specified: In Eugene's proposal these are specified through tags and they are (can be) more fine grained. In Mark's proposal these are specified at a much coarser level of extensions."}, {'account_id': 7576, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Temporary -1 for driver dynamic loading comment.'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-06-26 20:18:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for replies, Mark.

Based on your comment it seems metadata is then very close to tags, but resides on profile rather than in the flavor.

Another point I'd like to make that we may not need entry points in profiles and can use provider name, which is an alias for driver entry point any way. That way we save existing code of managing drivers."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-06-26 20:23:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Mohammad, on scheduling:

when the driver receives the create request, it gets flavor with the request payload, so it can use it's tags to alter behavior or configuration.
It is close to what is proposed here. The difference is that driver makes decision about configuration based on tags of the flavor where in this proposal whole configuration is decided by framework.

The basic difference is the workflow for operators."}, {'account_id': 7576, 'date': '2014-06-26 23:53:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

After thinking more on this proposal, there's a couple of simplifications I'd like to suggest:

1) It's really not necessary to have extensions on the flavor.
For the user that could be shown in the description.
As for implementation - I think we need to allow creating logical configuration regardless of implementation,
especially if we consider ability to migrate service from one implementation to another.

So, requests go through persistence layer and leave objects in PENDING_CREATE/UNSUPPORTED state.
Once implementation is appropriate, they will be deployed.

And for further development it would be easier to implement extension AND 
API aspects list via tags (so we will not have to redesign this part)

2) We don't need entry point on the profile.
We can use provider name as an alias to already loaded single instance of the driver.
This way we also avoid 'stateless' requirement for drivers and also 
preserve existing approach of loading drivers at startup.

I think this way we may make this proposal quite simple (and implementable in J-2) first step towards more flexible tag-based proposal."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-01 00:07:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

So let me ask the author of the spec and the reviewers with a vested interested in this patch a question. (vested interest == working on some adv service).

If we approve this patch today, how many chances do you think we have that the code is pushed, merged, and then leverage by at least one of the advanced services for the juno release?

commit_message:
Remove SQLAlchemy and alembic from requirements

Both are already pulled by oslo.db and Manila depends on the versions
required by oslo.db .

commit_message:
Removed deprecated 'shard' methods

Old shard methods were deprecated and a deprecation warning was being
raised in the current released version. I removed the deprecated shard
methods as well as the shard module.

Change-Id: I51dd839b566f5cbea03df9ab8500d9558282a59c
Closes-bug: #1395788

commit_message:
Reserve 49001/tcp port before starting swiftcheck

Require adding of '49001/tcp' port as reserved for swiftcheck
service to '/etc/services' before configuring it under xinetd.

Change-Id: Ia01959d205d186ce2e21afec9673df0fd6d94736
Closes-bug: #1462142

commit_message:
Update README to work with release tools

The README file needs to have links to the project documentation and bug
tracker in a parsable format in order for some of the release tools
scripts to work (particularly the one that prints the release note
email).

Change-Id: I37e0acc5ed8e1af565359290fa622456901c735e

Disable disassociate fip button when no fip associated

ip associated.

Closes-bug: #1462218

commit_message:
Add note about limitation of instances_path

If you want to "nova live-migration" with libvirt ,
not only use nfs for instances_path,
we have to specify same instances_path in each node which run nova-compute.

So I added note for this limitation of instances_path
Closes-Bug: #1460698

Change-Id: Ied3badabb2eff6d0428a0b6229ea8c5d1da4d9bd

commit_message:
pylint: enable `duplicate-key` check

This check attempts to detect dictionary literals with duplicate keys.

The rest of the Neutron tree has already had the few instances of this
cleaned[1] or moved into external vendor repos.  Enabling the pylint
check will stop future occurrences.

[1] I29cd2b843a7905986de13a1ecfba0cb5797ccaf8

(Original patch I1aa221d2019853f905f2b8421dd45b0a3102baf0 by zhiyuan_cai)

Change-Id: If4fed9714cd7fa586845f21f8f56dde2645cc5e0
Co-Authored-By: zhiyuan_cai <luckyvega.g@gmail.com>

@Henry and @Armando: Regarding https://review.openstack.org/187267
As per the current version of the above doc, it only covers monolithic plugins, ML2 mech drivers and L3 service plugins. 
This patch is proposed for an interface driver for a new VIF type. Are such drivers also supposed to be out of tree? 
If so, it is not clear how to handle this decomposition.'}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2015-06-04 11:46:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)

@Sourabh, don't panic. :) The goal for the core neutron code is to extract all vendor logic from it, but we are not going to throw your work under the bus. Follow this discussion with Armando and I and feel free to chime in with opinions and info. We'll work it out eventually, but if the discussions take too long I am sure your code can be given a pass in the interim."}, {'account_id': 7018, 'date': '2015-06-04 21:22:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

As usual, Armando is right. It looks pretty easy to do this patch entirely out-of-tree in the vendor repo. 

@Sourabh ping me if you need help.  This can serve as an example of how to set up rootwrap filters and interface drivers externally.

@Armando, I will add this info to the list of things I need to update the devref doc patch with. Hopefully I will have an update by Monday.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-06-05 01:21:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Henry, trust me! I am not :)

Armando'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-06-05 01:21:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Plug port into Cisco Nexus1000V switch

Cisco Nexus1000V supports binding ports using 'vemctl' script.
This proposed fix is to allow neutron to set up port bindings
using n1kv interface driver. Corresponding nova changes for vif
driver will be pushed up separately.

Change-Id: I03ec31d83bbeaa5729b45cbe7b257c61e9b197fa
Closes-Bug: 1423295

[{'created': '2015-06-03 16:59:01.000000000', 'message': 'Enhance utils.ensure_dir to be resilient to concurrent workers

In rare cases, concurrent workers may attempt to ensure a directory
exists.  One may successfully create the directory while the other
gets an oserror that it already exists.  This patch detects the
problem and returns successfully in both cases.

Change-Id: I224be69168ede8a496a5f7d59b04b722f4de7192
'}]
commit_message:
Enhance utils.ensure_dir to be resilient to concurrent workers

In rare cases, concurrent workers may attempt to ensure a directory
exists.  One may successfully create the directory while the other
gets an oserror that it already exists.  This patch detects the
problem and returns successfully in both cases.

Change-Id: I224be69168ede8a496a5f7d59b04b722f4de7192

commit_message:
Non-admin user to query volume filter by az

Now cinder limits non-admin user to query volume just filtered by 'name',
'status', and 'metadata', those are hard coded in cinder-api. So improve
this using config option and allow non-admin to query volume filtered by
'availability zone'.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia4a324959e16d7e6effe7afb18fe57562231d879
Implements: blueprint allow-non-admin-to-query-volume-filter-by-az

the subnet allocation pool based on some internal logic. So the check
should be that the port got ANY IP from the subnet allocation pool.

a network to 2 DHCP agents or more - two DHCP ports are created (while
the test expects one DHCP port) and the port created by the test may get
only the third IP address from the subnet allocation pool.

commit_message:
Fixing some tests for DHCP IPv6

The problem is that some tests in tempest/api/network/test_dhcp_ipv6.py
have wrong assumption on which exact IP a port will receive on the DHCP
enabled subnet. This is wrong because Neutron may assign ANY IP from
the subnet allocation pool based on some internal logic. So the check
should be that the port got ANY IP from the subnet allocation pool.

test_dhcp_ipv6.NetworksTestDHCPv6.test_dhcpv6_64_subnets
test_dhcp_ipv6.NetworksTestDHCPv6.test_dhcpv6_two_subnets
test_dhcp_ipv6.NetworksTestDHCPv6.test_dhcp_stateful

In these tests the assumption is that the port will receive the first
or second IP address from the subnet allocation pool. But we can schedule
a network to 2 DHCP agents or more - two DHCP ports are created (while
the test expects one DHCP port) and the port created by the test may get
only the third IP address from the subnet allocation pool.

Closes-Bug: #1458878

Change-Id: I655f803aa96509e95d52e8288395714c88b9e3b4

'}]
commit_message:
Fix argument handling in oslo_run_cross_tests

If there are no arguments the shift call fails, aborting before we can
report the proper usage instructions. Update the script to check the
argument count before trying to do anything with them.

fix usage property(vcpus, vcpu_hours) error use

Change usage property vpcus and vcpu_hours,
vcpus describe vcpu num, vcpu_hours describe
vcpu hours

Closes-bug:#1416984

commit_message:
Modifying "swift post" command to display help

"swift post" doesnot display help if any
argument is not given. This behaviour/semantics
is not consistent with other swift commands
(like swift upload). So account name is made
mandatory for the "swift post" command.

Change-Id: I9c554ac03874afd936db796c35beedc7e3e1d459

commit_message:
Do not verify requirements on extension loading

The heat gate is broken due to other libraries pinning
on pbr<1.0

Stevedore extension loading currently has verify_requirements=True.
This change removes this to use the default of False. Loading extensions
is likely the wrong place to be enforcing requirements versions of
libraries that heat depends on, so lets not do it.

This is likely to also improve heat robustness for deployments with
inconsistent dependencies, not just this current heat breakage.

commit_message:
Implements the haproxy amphora agent api server

- Added configuration
- Added uploading of haproxy config
- Added start, stop, reload (async)
- Added get_details
- Fixed returns of API -- they are now all spec conform
- Added info, get haproxy file
- Added function to get listener status
- Added class to parse haproxy stats socket
- Added methods to handle certs
- Added client cert validation to the sever
- Added script to generate example certs
- Added init script for agent
- Added network and vip plugging
- Added devstack stuff
- Added diskimage scripts; upstart ini file

Change-Id: Ib1db8da9e019e68e9a0f4a16a622b8b1286afd3e
Implements: blueprint amphora-api

While I agree we need to do something with the post jobs because the results are too difficult to discover. But, I don't think emailing them to any list is the correct approach, especially the openstack-qa list which doesn't have many people following it. This method fails for the periodic jobs which the qa team has a vested interest in, which I can't say is the case for the post jobs.

I'm thinking a better path forward is to either have it report back to gerrit in a comment so it'll get picked up by the ci js, or construct a dashboard view to visualize when post jobs are failing. I also think this would be useful for perioidic jobs because aside from scrolling the ML logs its really difficult to find out what broke them."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-10-01 14:24:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Report failed post jobs to openstack-qa

If a post job fails we should probably know about it rather than
not reporting the logs back to anywhere.

Change-Id: I787661f22f65ecf5691275ed9d818d2b2a88ec79

Add docs tox env

'tox -edocs' and build the docs which get published to

commit_message:
configure pacemaker VIPs for isolated networks

This patch updates the overcloud pacemaker role manifest so
that it optionally configures VIPs on isolated networks if
they are enabled.

Change-Id: I6123ee622abe4d8d7b5f76cf9bac43acd80c1f64

[{'created': '2015-06-01 14:50:32.000000000', 'message': 'Set glance_api_servers for cinder

This patch updates the hiera configuration for the Cinder API so
that we set glance_api_servers. By default Cinder constructs
a glance URL based on $my_ip (the local IP of the machine)
which may not be correct if you are running Glance on a non-default
internal network.

By setting glance_api_servers to the same thing we already
use for Nova we make Cinder contact the correct Glance URL
regardless of the network settings.

Change-Id: I1c56eb585ddfdc9989a8b55bc1bac819802f7794

commit_message:
Set glance_api_servers for cinder

This patch updates the hiera configuration for the Cinder API so
that we set glance_api_servers. By default Cinder constructs
a glance URL based on $my_ip (the local IP of the machine)
which may not be correct if you are running Glance on a non-default
internal network.

By setting glance_api_servers to the same thing we already
use for Nova we make Cinder contact the correct Glance URL
regardless of the network settings.

Change-Id: I1c56eb585ddfdc9989a8b55bc1bac819802f7794

commit_message:
Add findall server side filtering

Findall method in cinderclient/base.py isn't very efficient: it loads
the entire list then filters on the Python side. When calling "cinder
show 'volName'" on a tenant holding a lot of volumes (> 1000) the run
time is too long.

On my env show command with 10000 volumes takes ~2 min, after apply
this patch few seconds.

Closes-Bug: #1449444

commit_message:
Raise InstanceNotFound when save FK constraint fails

Currently, in the Instance.save method, if an ObjectField is dirty,
it will be updated in the db before the instance record is updated
(separate transaction). If the instance does not have a row, the
foreign key constraint fails and DBReferenceError is raised from
oslo.db. This scenario can happen in cells if an instance delete
request comes in before it's scheduled, during the broadcast to
delete in all cells. This is expected and InstanceNotFound is
caught and handled.

This change catches DBReferenceError and raises InstanceNotFound.

Closes-Bug: #1462128

Change-Id: I821f8c121760e0fb74d7ae5c680bd0c361f92128

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-01 14:50:32.000000000', 'message': 'puppet controller role: per service VIP settings

This patch refactors the puppet controller role so that it
makes use of per service VIP settings for each service.

Previously the VIP for the ctlplane was hard wired to
many of the controller service. With this patch we have
the ability to isolate traffic for services which
made use of the ctlplane and public VIPs for their
settings.

The implementation includes:

 * stops the use of the VirtualIP and PublicVirtualIP within the
   controller role. These parameters have now been replaced with
   per service heat parameters for the controller nested stack which
   are determined via VipMap based on per service settings in the heat
   environment.

 * All VIP configuration is now moved into puppet/vip-config.yaml.
   This made sense so we could deprecate the use of the VirtualIP
   and PublicVirtualIP settings above.

 * The puppet manifests for the controller were cleaned up for several
   to use Hiera directly instead of constructing URLs based on the
   static controller and public network VIPs. This improvement
   was something we wanted to do anyways and made the implementation
   cleaner.

Change-Id: I9b9a15be67f74bec97366408f7047acfd6ea0ec6

commit_message:
puppet controller role: per service VIP settings

This patch refactors the puppet controller role so that it
makes use of per service VIP settings for each service.

Previously the VIP for the ctlplane was hard wired to
many of the controller service. With this patch we have
the ability to isolate traffic for services which
made use of the ctlplane and public VIPs for their
settings.

The implementation includes:

 * stops the use of the VirtualIP and PublicVirtualIP within the
   controller role. These parameters have now been replaced with
   per service heat parameters for the controller nested stack which
   are determined via VipMap based on per service settings in the heat
   environment.

 * All VIP configuration is now moved into puppet/vip-config.yaml.
   This made sense so we could deprecate the use of the VirtualIP
   and PublicVirtualIP settings above.

 * The puppet manifests for the controller were cleaned up for several
   to use Hiera directly instead of constructing URLs based on the
   static controller and public network VIPs. This improvement
   was something we wanted to do anyways and made the implementation
   cleaner.

Change-Id: I9b9a15be67f74bec97366408f7047acfd6ea0ec6

commit_message:
Use os-brick library

This spec lays out the process for which we remove the internals
of the libvirt volume drivers to use the new os-brick library that
has been incubated inside of Cinder since the Havana release cycle.

Cinder has been updated to use the os-brick library already.

Change-Id: Ia5ea709dc4749e207b0278e5d5096ba0154a31d8
Blueprint: use-os-brick-library

commit_message:
Order routes so most frequent requests are first

Since authentication is going to be the most common operation in a real
environment, I moved this first.

The problem is that routes uses one, yes one, huge regex for
dispatching. This is not performant for the unfortunate routes that
appear at the end.

Change-Id: I06bc2fa6a29934e28ab83d92bc9bf9b3665ba34c

      </iotune>

commit_message:
libvirt:add instance disk IO control for rbd backend

We support instance disk IO control through libvirt domain element
<iotune> like:
      <iotune>
        <total_bytes_sec>102400</total_bytes_sec>
      </iotune>

Abstract class Image's method libvirt_info set the iotune values from
instance extra_specs. Class Rbd overwrites the method libvirt_info and
doesn't add the logic of adding disk IO control. Let's add the logic.

Closes-Bug: #1461414
Change-Id: I6df279d2b2d3215269bb248ec200983b0cb562e7

commit_message:
Validates the number of data/parity on EC

For now, PyECLib/liberausrecode doesn't work well
when decoding a segment from only parity fragments
and it definitly causes a GET object failure.

To prevent it (and wait the fix merged on PyECLib),
we should validate the number of data/parity on EC
as a constraint.

e.g.:

from pyeclib.ec_iface import ECDriver

driver = ECDriver(k=10, m=10, ec_type='jerarure_rs_vand')
encoded = driver.encode(' ')
driver.decode(encoded[10:])  # fail with core dumped

See the fix[1] in detail.

When the fix merged and using the newest PyECLib,
we would be able to remove this constraint so this is a
temporary way to prevent the unfortunate cases until the
fix released.

1: https://bitbucket.org/tsg-/liberasurecode/pull-request/15

Change-Id: I189dcb422155e35800b0001781242d3d12caa94f

commit_message:
Cleanup subunit capture in run-tox.sh

This commit cleans up the subunit capture section of run-tox to
accomplish 2 things. First make the output naming consistent with
dsvm jobs and call the subunit output testrepository.subunit. The
second is to avoid using subunit-1to2 directly. A subunit v2 stream
can be achieved directly from testr last by using the --subunit
flag.

Change-Id: Ica644535f54e28306f4db97217b77f95d2f5943b

I don't understand your explanation.  As far as I can determine, we only try to do something with the retry_after attribute on an exception if it descends from RetryAfterException, and nothing in novaclient (other than tests) ever references the retry_after attribute on an exception after it's set.  Where is this secondary traceback occurring?  What is the original traceback?

I have no trouble with the idea of making Forbidden extend RetryAfterException, since we are sending a Retry-After header; I just don't have enough information from the commit message to understand the problem this is intended to solve…"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-05 00:26:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Nova will send a retry-after header when dealing with Over Quota
situations. Client code was not prepared to handle this and would cause
a secondary traceback to happen and would mask the original error. Move

'}]
commit_message:
Handle retry-after headers in 403 errors

Nova will send a retry-after header when dealing with Over Quota
situations. Client code was not prepared to handle this and would cause
a secondary traceback to happen and would mask the original error. Move
Forbidden (the 403) handler to subclass from RetryAfterException so that
the retry-after header is properly processed.

Change-Id: I5fc8a3123857e20acac3fdee17a760f457ab0b91

commit_message:
ngReorg - move utils from dashboad-app

This will facilitate the removal of dashboard-app from
horizon-the-framework.

The "tech-debt" folder is intended to be removed in subsequent
patches (still to be created) which move or remove the functions
in that folder. The reason for not doing so now is that there
would be functionality changes, and I wanted to keep this patch
as small as possible.

The dummy controller also moves to the same place as it
is an empty controller that will eventually go away when
the Django modal it's used in goes away.

Change-Id: I0b89205b9c6c7b1498c1a3c48e53ba460b9e5469
Partial-Bug: #1458697

commit_message:
Bump docker-py version for new exec call

Docker-py would soon deprecated the execute method, instead
they suggest to use exec_start and exec_create
refer: http://docker-py.readthedocs.org/en/1.2.2/change_log/#120
So we need bump version to 1.2.0

commit_message:
Federated domain identified by ``id`` not ``name``

Ephemeral users are by default members of a service domain
``Federated``. Keystone code uses attribute ``id`` to identify this
domain in the user object. Examples in documentation used ``name``
attribute. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I6639c94d6c12053b0fe93fbe860f35c48688f426
Closes-Bug: #1461031

fixed.

[{'created': '2015-04-23 16:29:20.000000000', 'message': "Don't register https endpoints for non-ssl services

The current code always registers endpoints as https if there is a
public_endpoint set.  For services that don't currently support ssl,
that results in an https url pointing at a non-https port.  This
change checks for both a public_host and ssl_port setting and only
uses ssl if both are present.

Change-Id: Ibeb038eaaf7faea90c2881834c5d675759cedbb3
"}]
commit_message:
Don't register https endpoints for non-ssl services

The current code always registers endpoints as https if there is a
public_endpoint set.  For services that don't currently support ssl,
that results in an https url pointing at a non-https port.  This
change checks for both a public_host and ssl_port setting and only
uses ssl if both are present.

Change-Id: Ibeb038eaaf7faea90c2881834c5d675759cedbb3

commit_message:
Reduced kafka metrics in the default case

Previously metrics were per partition per consumer which can quickly get
quite large. Now they default to per topic rather than per partition.

Change-Id: I6fe2bd57ddcfbb89c907dc7c2f9781bdd23db6ce

commit_message:
Add share shrink API

Implement optional API for shrinking shares:
"manila shrink <share-id> <new-size>"

- Implement tenant-facing API for shrinking shares
- Add appropriate unit tests

Partially implements bp share-shrink-api

Change-Id: I48f8e05793a992b11fb180b0b4dbf43bcffb4229

commit_message:
Fixes for Python 3

Nova is working on support for Python 3.4. via
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/nova-python3

This changeset moves from py33 to py34 in the tox.ini file to be
inline with Nova. It also incorporates changes produced from the
'sixer' tool run with 'all'.

sixer can be found at:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

At the present time, the py34 environment does not run
successfully because it pulls in portions of Nova that have not
yet been fully converted to Python 3.

Change-Id: If84df3017a722d0ad3546e81f97e67f1a07a763f
